</style>在乌克兰炎热的夏日，两个名叫帖木儿和斯拉维克的小男孩正在卡霍夫卡水库（第聂伯河的一部分）岸边玩耍。我七月份访问该地区时遇到了他们。空气中的宁静偶尔会被不远处前线城镇的战斗声打破。该地区是乌克兰反攻的焦点，六月有证据表明，俄罗斯人为了减缓敌人的前进，炸毁了卡霍夫卡大坝。<br><br>我想亲眼目睹这场灾难。很快人们就清楚地意识到，这次塌陷将重塑未来几十年的地貌。大坝以南的一切都被浑浊的河水吞没了。<br><br>下游的赫尔松市，洪水迫使数千人和动物撤离，其中许多人遭到俄罗斯炮火的袭击。大坝东北部的水库已变成一片贫瘠、泥泞的平原，一直延伸到地平线。当与俄罗斯的敌对行动停止后，乌克兰面临的挑战又增加了从这场环境灾难中进行重建的任务。<br><br>卡霍夫卡水库建于 20 世纪 50 年代，其规模接近犹他州大盐湖，为整个乌克兰南部和克里米亚半岛供水。大坝的水灌溉农场和果园，大坝水电站产生的电力用于整个地区的村庄。扎波罗热核电站还使用水库水来冷却其反应堆。现在这一切都消失了。取而代之的是农业和渔业的不确定的未来。<br><br>有一天，我和一位正在栅栏后面洗车的老人开始了交谈。他的家距离原来的水库岸线不远。鲍勃·迪伦正在用一个小扬声器演奏。这个自称叫伊霍尔的男人邀请我到他的屋顶上勘察现场。 “从周围的任何屋顶都看不到我们的新沙漠的景色，”他告诉我。当太阳开始落山时，我们一起坐在他的别墅顶上，我现在看到的是一幅超现实的月球景观。 <br><br><img alt="一对情侣在岩石海滩上拥抱" height="663" src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/lx5hGxAxHP7IRs-F9TLiVsLmK4w=/928x663/media/img/posts/2023/07/JN05_The_Atlantic_230628_Kakhovka_Dam_Final_Edit/original.jpg" srcset="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/lx5hGxAxHP7IRs-F9TLiVsLmK4w=/928x663/media/img/posts/2023/07/JN05_The_Atlantic_230628_Kakhovka_Dam_Final_Edit/original.jpg, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/OdAkLUpdeMtZ3l0cm6oTPXfUVB0=/1856x1326/media/img/posts/2023/07/JN05_The_Atlantic_230628_Kakhovka_Dam_Final_Edit/original.jpg 2x" width="928" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption class="caption">扎波罗热，一对情侣在第聂伯河曾经流过的河水处拥抱。 </figcaption><img alt="TK" height="412" src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/nm-C-5E-mbgj_Z5ZiotD6GeDpkY=/928x412/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_2a/original.jpg" srcset="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/nm-C-5E-mbgj_Z5ZiotD6GeDpkY=/928x412/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_2a/original.jpg, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/nqqIdNPziCkvvZ57v5lC4e0eifs=/1856x824/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_2a/original.jpg 2x" width="928" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption class="caption">在玛丽安斯克村，水库边缘的一座桥梁被炸毁。自战争开始以来，摧毁桥梁一直是乌克兰各地采用的战略策略。 </figcaption><img alt="TK" height="412" src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/VKQNItkBvx08Pun2QgpKm6PEhAE=/928x412/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_2b/original.jpg" srcset="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/VKQNItkBvx08Pun2QgpKm6PEhAE=/928x412/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_2b/original.jpg, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/dmLxHXLNj6wLcaFqSfqLmuSlTU0=/1856x824/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_2b/original.jpg 2x" width="928" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption class="caption">卡霍夫卡大坝被毁后奥莱克西夫卡村的居民</figcaption><img alt="TK" height="412" src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/FfpPcAllIxfX7buvuATBm1iClSU=/928x412/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_2c/original.jpg" srcset="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/FfpPcAllIxfX7buvuATBm1iClSU=/928x412/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_2c/original.jpg, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/JzIxeeD932jYIjgN9eZuwQNJMGI=/1856x824/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_2c/original.jpg 2x" width="928" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption class="caption">奥列克西夫卡，一名妇女从干涸的河水中取水。 </figcaption><img alt="广阔的干旱景观" height="663" src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/S8_M9xPrQKw5cc-8WUPuPw1AnFk=/928x663/media/img/posts/2023/07/JN015_The_Atlantic_230711_Kakhovka_Dam_Final_Edit/original.jpg" srcset="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/S8_M9xPrQKw5cc-8WUPuPw1AnFk=/928x663/media/img/posts/2023/07/JN015_The_Atlantic_230711_Kakhovka_Dam_Final_Edit/original.jpg, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/ci62BRj0d6rO2ZnY1QMBh6GL-LY=/1856x1326/media/img/posts/2023/07/JN015_The_Atlantic_230711_Kakhovka_Dam_Final_Edit/original.jpg 2x" width="928" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption class="caption">卡霍夫卡水库干涸的底部</figcaption><img alt="tkk" height="412" src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/1FO_JnsF3_tRtKLb4E_agCD8RK4=/928x412/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_3a/original.jpg" srcset="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/1FO_JnsF3_tRtKLb4E_agCD8RK4=/928x412/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_3a/original.jpg, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/3ErxmFR69Z4yCpU0IlFbqP9NAjQ=/1856x824/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_3a/original.jpg 2x" width="928" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption class="caption">在苏希乔托姆利克河上，人们正在努力获取剩余的水。 </figcaption><img alt="tkk" height="412" src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/wvzSQtHCMKVFnPj_o_Vc3xIq-mI=/928x412/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_3b/original.jpg" srcset="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/wvzSQtHCMKVFnPj_o_Vc3xIq-mI=/928x412/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_3b/original.jpg, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/xYtB5soEr8fHsu0OEHqXHj3iz6M=/1856x824/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_3b/original.jpg 2x" width="928" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption class="caption">尼科波尔的居民从市中心的一个人道主义援助点获得饮用水。该市一直在解决水龙头缺水的问题。 </figcaption><img alt="干旱地区的一头牛" height="412" src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/-UHYppvVO5_ktuKUdyDYRrhO3GY=/928x412/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_3c/original.jpg" srcset="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/-UHYppvVO5_ktuKUdyDYRrhO3GY=/928x412/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_3c/original.jpg, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/HHZjv8Uqtk1h2WmuodyEnFRg3pw=/1856x824/media/img/posts/2023/07/Untitled_3c/original.jpg 2x" width="928" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption class="caption">一头牛在 Malokaterynivka 村的一个农场里吃草，背景是干涸的卡霍夫卡水库。 </figcaption><img alt="tkk" height="663" src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/S1ohTpP0Z3ag_QUNynQVN0g5tDY=/928x663/media/img/posts/2023/07/JN028_The_Atlantic_230611_Kakhovka_Dam_Final_Edit/original.jpg" srcset="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/S1ohTpP0Z3ag_QUNynQVN0g5tDY=/928x663/media/img/posts/2023/07/JN028_The_Atlantic_230611_Kakhovka_Dam_Final_Edit/original.jpg, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/V7JKGl68Gk7cw7p2Uf87wvfqh_s=/1856x1326/media/img/posts/2023/07/JN028_The_Atlantic_230611_Kakhovka_Dam_Final_Edit/original.jpg 2x" width="928" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption class="caption">卡霍夫卡水库退去的水</figcaption></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/ukraine-kakhovka-dam-destruction-gallery/674806/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/ukraine-kakhovka-dam-destruction-gallery/674806/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Dear Therapist: My Husband Had a Relationship With His Best Friend]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>他所说的这个对他来说“像兄弟一样”的人，事实证明他的意义远不止于此。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/Gjv56aDhFbpjwlv5rI1BK1uXHms=/0x0:4950x2784/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/My_Husband_Used_to_Sleep_With_His_Male_Best_Friend_final/original.jpg" alt="一幅插图，描绘了一对躺在床上的丈夫和妻子，他们之间有一个像植物一样的人，拥抱着丈夫" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>比安卡·巴格纳雷利插图</figcaption></figure><strong>亲爱的治疗师，</strong><br><br>我和我丈夫结婚一年了，在此之前我们约会了三年。他与前妻结婚20多年，育有一个孩子。在他第一次结婚之前，我听说过他的许多前女友，而且我知道他在婚姻结束后、和我约会之前有过一个女朋友。<br><br>他还有一个最好的朋友，一个住在我们隔壁的人。我们婚礼几周后，我在文件柜里找地方存放我从以前家带来的一些文件，我看到一张纸卡在滚轮里。上面写着“[他最好朋友的名字]喜欢[我丈夫的名字]。”我想知道这是怎么回事，所以我侵犯了他的隐私。我发现了这位朋友写给我丈夫的许多卡片和情书，日期是我们结婚前 12 年左右。<br><br>我哭了，很震惊。我和我的丈夫交谈，他说，在与结婚二十年的妻子离婚后，他很受伤。他想要的不是女人，而是一个伴侣。我发现他在那段时间（大约四年）与几个男人交谈过，直到他努力克服自己的感情。他让他最好的朋友搬出了他的房子，但那个朋友仍然住在我们隔壁，在我丈夫家的财产上。我必须每天都被提醒他们之间发生的事情。他们在一起时发生了性关系，现在当我看着他们两个时，这就是我所能想象的。<br><br>我知道我进入这个圈子已经过去了大约十年，但我很痛苦。我丈夫说他对他的朋友不再有任何浪漫的感觉了。我丈夫是独生子，他说这个最好的朋友就像兄弟一样。<br><br>这一切都让我很烦恼。距离我知道已经一年多了，我似乎仍然无法接受我的丈夫。我能做些什么来克服这个问题？我的丈夫对每个人都充满爱心和友善。他对我和我的女儿很好，并且热爱他和我的家人。但我一直看到他过去的错误。他说那是他的过去，发生在我出现之前。尽管如此，每天被提醒还是很困难。<br><br><strong>匿名的</strong><br><br><strong>亲爱的匿名者，</strong><br><br>一段关系中最令人不安的经历之一就是发现某些事情并不像看上去的那样。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/02/how-to-tell-child-sperm-donor/673194/">秘密的发现</a>会让你重新评估你自以为了解的关于伴侣的一切，并让你质疑你的现实感和你自以为共同的信任。<br><br>对你来说，还有一个额外的层面，即两个秘密同时被揭露。首先，你丈夫最亲密的朋友也是他的前任。其次，你的丈夫曾与男性发生过关系。尽管这两个事实都让你感到困惑和被背叛，但对你来说，单独考虑你对这些发现的反应很重要，以便找出如何继续前进并从这些欺骗中治愈。<br><br>关于第一点，你的丈夫与你只认识他最好的朋友的人有一段浪漫的关系，而你却因疏忽的谎言而感到震惊。暂时把性别放在一边（因为我们接下来会讨论这个问题），你没有被告知某个与他非常亲近并且作为你的隔壁邻居出现在你的生活中的人与你的丈夫有性史。这并不是“哎呀，我忘了提及”的疏忽，而是故意阻止您发现。我说性别不是这里的问题，因为即使这个人是女性，我想如果你没有被告知他最亲密的朋友（也住在你的共同财产上）也是他的前任，你也会感到被背叛。<br><br>当你的信任被破坏后，你感到痛苦是有道理的。尽管你们就自己的发现进行了交谈，并且您的丈夫也坦白了自己的历史，但仍需要采取更多措施来修复他的不诚实造成的损害。例如，他有没有告诉过你为什么他没有告诉你他和他最好的朋友的恋情，以及他将来会采取什么措施来诚实？无论出于何种原因，他是否对隐瞒此事承担全部责任？ （“是的，我撒谎了，但这是因为 X”和“我因为 X 撒了谎，但无论如何，我不应该撒谎，我承诺将来对你诚实”之间是有区别的。 ) 你有没有与他分享过，当你们一起开始婚姻时，他对这个秘密的掌握让你感觉如何不受束缚，以及你对未来的诚实期望是什么？<br><br>当你们进行这样的谈话时，你需要带着好奇和同情心来倾听，这并不意味着你不追究他欺骗你的责任。相反，您正在创建一个可以在你们之间培养更多信任的环境。例如，他可能会说他不敢告诉你，因为他相信你会因为前任每天的出现而感到威胁，并希望他结束一段对他来说非常重要的友谊，而他感到在披露和失去他之间陷入了困境。最好的朋友。他可能会说他担心如果你知道他被男人吸引，你可能会拒绝他甚至离开他（考虑到你的反应，他可能是对的）。反过来，你可能会告诉他，他隐藏了与他经常互动的前任的相关信息，这让你想知道他还可能隐藏了什么，并质疑你是否可以信任他：他是否分享了他们过去和现在的全部情况关系？难道他还隐藏着其他与这个人无关的秘密？<br><br>当你说话时，确保你不仅对他完全诚实，而且对你自己也完全诚实。你需要反思什么能让你在未来几年感到安全，并将其传达给他。这可能包括对他与他最好的朋友的关系进行全面的说明，以便以后故事的更多方面不会被泄露，他现在与您分享任何明显的遗漏谎言，这样就不会再出现任何意外（您可以将此描述为“如果有什么我想知道的，现在是时候告诉我了，因为稍后告诉我可能会让我无法再次信任你或和你在一起”），并进行夫妻治疗来共同解决这个问题。这些只是建议——你必须决定你真正需要什么，并提出要求。<br><br>您还可以讨论您对当前生活安排的感受。如果一开始就没有秘密，这可能不是问题，但现在可能会成为问题，因为你的信任已经破裂。也许你对他们持续的友谊感到满意，但希望前任不住在隔壁，或者考虑到他们恋爱多久了，你可能对这种接近感到满意。当您回答这个问题时，需要考虑一下当您说“每天都想起”您丈夫的前任很难时，您的意思是什么。哪一个提醒对你来说是困难的：他和你生活中的前任有过一段浪漫的过去，他为此欺骗了你，或者前任是个男人？<br><br>这让我想到了第二个秘密——你丈夫对男人的吸引力——这对你们俩来说似乎都更复杂。你和你的丈夫似乎都对自己的性取向感到不舒服。在与前任约会并与几个男人交谈了四年之后，你说“他努力克服自己的感情”，这表明他感到羞耻或否认，而你的不赞成和判断在你称他与一个男人约会时表现出来“他过去的错误”——这是你不会对他的任何前女友说的话。你们似乎都不愿意承认你的丈夫对男人和女人都有吸引力，你需要检查你丈夫的性取向会给你们俩带来什么，这样这些感觉就不会导致更多的秘密。<br><br>您可以首先探索为什么您“似乎无法接受”他，并澄清您对双性恋的任何误解或假设。也许你认为这意味着他将永远怀念与男人在一起的时光，因此可能会欺骗你——这不是性吸引力的运作方式。正如你总是会被其他人所吸引一样，他也会如此；关键是，如果你们都选择一夫一妻制的关系，你们都不会按照这些愿望行事。你可以请他与你分享他作为一个同时被男人和女人吸引的人的经历，以便他能够澄清他的性取向对他意味着什么。你可以谈论你们各自的历史，以及关于同性伙伴关系的文化或家庭耻辱，以及这些观点如何演变，以便你的丈夫有空间被你充分地爱着他真实的自我——一个似乎被吸引的男人男性和女性，以及一夫一妻制婚姻。如果你强迫他隐藏真实的自我，你就会鼓励他更多地保守秘密，并使你的丈夫为自己的身份感到羞耻。你可能需要花一些时间试图理解（也许在治疗师的帮助下）你所爱并被吸引的男人是如何在你的脑海中变成另一个人的——一个你厌恶的人——因为他有过一段与他交往的历史。与他同性别的伴侣。<br><br>有时我们不会谈论我们最需要讨论的事情，因为一旦承认事实，我们就无法不承认它。现在，你们俩的表现就好像你们的丈夫对男人不感兴趣，甚至在他与男人发生性关系时也没有（相反，你写道他在离婚的过程中想要“一个伴侣”）。如果你想要一段基于诚实的婚姻，回避真相是没有帮助的。<br><br>事实是这样的：你丈夫的浪漫过去是他的一部分，就像你的过去是你的一部分一样。我们都希望在婚姻中展现出完整的自我，并因为真实的自己而被爱和接受。既然秘密已经公开，不要否认它们对你所结婚的人意味着什么，而是一起拥抱真相，尽管它的复杂性和不适性，这样你就可以以你所渴望的信任和开放来建立这段新的婚姻。<br><br> <em>《亲爱的治疗师》仅供参考，不构成医疗建议，也不能替代专业的医疗建议、诊断或治疗。如果您对健康状况有任何疑问，请务必寻求您的医生、心理健康专家或其他合格的医疗服务提供者的建议。提交信件即表示您同意</em>《大西洋月刊》<em>使用该信件的部分或全部内容，我们可能会对其长度和/或清晰度进行编辑。</em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/husband-best-friend-relationship-advice-trust/674858/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/husband-best-friend-relationship-advice-trust/674858/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Show That Knows the Secret to Serialized TV]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Yair Rosenberg 的娱乐必备<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/1IJm7MhDj5qxKLJ7SjLICWbQ9bA=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/babylon_5/original.jpg" alt="巴比伦5号空间站图片" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>华纳兄弟。</figcaption></figure><small><i data-stringify-type="italic">这是</i>《大西洋<i data-stringify-type="italic">日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">在这里注册。</a></i></small><br><br>欢迎回到《每日邮报》的周日文化版，一位<i>大西洋月刊的</i>作家在其中揭示了是什么让他们开心。<br><br>今天的特邀嘉宾是<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>特约撰稿人亚伊尔·罗森伯格。 Yair 撰写有关政治、文化和宗教交集的文章，也是我们的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/">Deep Shtetl</a>时事通讯的作者。他最近揭示了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/israel-supreme-court-netanyahu-parliament/674833/">以色列社会信任崩溃的情况</a>，提供了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-threads-new-suggested-rules/674709/">建立更好的社交媒体平台</a>的路线图， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/6494bbb2a1d6420038c5cb21/congress-antisemitism-yair-rosenberg/">在国会就反犹太主义作证</a>，并与演员本普拉特谈论了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/641c6dfed18ff80037f5eb02/ben-platt-parade-interview-yair-rosenberg-jews/">犹太教在表演者作品中所扮演的角色。百老汇</a>。亚伊尔目前正在创作一部独特的科幻短篇小说集，尽管给洋基队带来了巨大的痛苦，但仍为洋基队加油，并回忆了一项已不复存在的神奇科技。<br><br>首先，这是<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>的三篇周日读物：<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/sound-of-freedom-qanon-culture-war/674832/">“我看了‘他们’不想让你看的电影。”</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-ken/674852/">芭比就是一切。肯就是其他一切。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/sinead-oconnor-legacy-mandinka-song/674844/">这首歌曲首次俘获了西妮德·奥康纳的力量</a></li><b>文化调查：Yair Rosenberg</b><br><br><b>我十几岁时就喜欢的一种文化产品：</b>在高中时，我最珍贵的财产之一是便携式 DVD 播放器。这正是它听起来的样子：带有屏幕的翻盖设备，可以播放光盘上的电影。拥有一台意味着我可以在学校越野旅行时观看<i>《指环王》</i> ，或者躲在自己的房间里狂看 Netflix 的电视节目（那时他们还给你寄 DVD）。我费了好大劲才说服父母帮我拿到那东西，以前我去哪儿都带着它。如今，便携式播放器已成为博物馆藏品，早已被功能更强大、播放更高质量视频的智能手机所取代。但再多的处理能力或像素分辨率也无法取代公交车上那个可以点播电影的怪孩子的魔力。<br><br><b>我最近重新观看、重读或以其他方式重温的东西：</b>我最喜欢的电视节目之一是一部古怪的 90 年代科幻传奇，名为<i>《巴比伦 5》</i> 。该剧的独特之处在于其创作者 J. Michael Straczynski 提前规划了整个五年的故事情节。他基本上写了整部小说，然后将其搬上银幕。正如我为<i>《大西洋月刊》</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/harry-potter-hbo-reboot-tv-series-jk-rowling/673816/">所写的</a>那样，当今大多数连续剧电视节目都令我失望。他们的情节往往不会成功，因为编剧们都是边编边编。 <i>《迷失》</i>就是一个典型的例子，但还有很多其他例子。 <i>《巴比伦5》</i>则相反，它不断地预示事件——有时甚至提前整季——并带领角色踏上可信的成长、发现和悲剧之旅。我一直在重温这部剧，因为它很令人愉快，而且还因为斯特拉钦斯基将于下个月以<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt27712788/">原创动画电影</a>的形式发布这个故事的新部分。<br><br><b>我最喜欢的大片和最喜欢的艺术电影：</b>我是那些不仅在前面提到的便携式 DVD 播放器上观看每部<i>《指环王》</i>电影的加长版，而且还与所有演员和工作人员一起观看多次的人之一评论。这就是我知道重要事情的方式，比如当布景设计师试图为角色在被洪水淹没的艾辛格堡垒中创造一条漂浮的苹果路径时，制作是如何暂时中断的，结果苹果拒绝漂浮。最终，他们意识到自己被设计完美的蜡制道具水果愚弄了。<br><br>我在聚会上很受欢迎。<br><br>至于艺术电影，这可能是一种作弊，但我会选择<i>脚注</i>。这是一部外语电影，所以从定义上来说并不是一部大片，但它确实赢得了以色列相当于奥斯卡奖的最佳影片奖，并且在 2012 年获得了真正的奥斯卡最佳外语片奖。正如我<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/6351cf31fb1fdd00362a68d8/guide-jewish-history-culture-anti-semitism/">在其他地方</a>所说的那样，“它是可以肯定地说，导演约瑟夫·西达的<i>《脚注》</i>是您看过的唯一一部获得奥斯卡提名的关于塔木德学者的戏剧喜剧。这也是一部关于父子、代际冲突以及古往今来犹太文本激发的激情的非凡电影。”这部电影取材于现实生活中的一个学术王朝，其成员包括我自己的亲戚，这并没有什么坏处。 <b>[相关：</b> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/6351cf31fb1fdd00362a68d8/guide-jewish-history-culture-anti-semitism/">如何从犹太人而不是讨厌他们的人那里了解犹太人</a><b>]</b><br><br><b>我什么都会看的演员：</b>彼得·萨斯加德。他拥有令人难以置信的魅力和范围，无论是在《<i>破碎的玻璃》</i> （有史以来关于现代新闻业的最佳电影）中扮演一位顽强的杂志编辑，揭露他的一位明星记者的寓言，还是在<i>《教育》</i>中体现一个掠夺性但具有磁性的骗子艺术家，<i> </i>诱捕一位易受影响的大学生（由伟大的凯瑞·穆里根扮演）和她的家人。<br><br><b>我最近读过的最好的小说作品：</b>我一直在努力阅读一本新的科幻短篇小说选集，名为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/jewish-futures-science-fiction-from-the-world-s-oldest-diaspora-michael-a-burstein/9781515458050?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《犹太未来》</i></a> 。它将于下个月发布，但我在 Kickstarter 上支持了该项目，所以我得到了一份预发本。我迫不及待地想让其他人能够阅读它——不仅仅是因为我姐姐对此做出了贡献。与所有选集一样，不同的故事会向不同的读者讲述，但迄今为止我最喜欢的是 Leah Cypess 的搞笑《Frummer House》，讲述了当智能家居开始对其居民强加宗教仪式时会发生什么； 《The Ascent》是亚伯拉罕·约瑟芬·里斯曼 (Abraham Josephine Riesman) 和 SI·罗森鲍姆 (SI Rosenbaum) 创作的关于耶路撒冷永恒修复和毁灭的令人难忘的故事；当然，还有我姐姐 SM Rosenberg 的《月亮旋律》，它是米德拉什和超级英雄故事的结合体。<br><br><b>最后一个让我哭泣的文化或娱乐事件：</b>纽约洋基队的进攻，或者更确切地说，缺乏进攻。<br><br><b>我最近收到的一个很好的文化或娱乐建议：</b>停止观看洋基队。我没有听。<br><br><b>一位对我来说意义重大的音乐艺术家：</b>我喜欢爱尔兰民间音乐——它的合唱品质、它的代际吸引力、它反映和延续文化记忆的方式。我会听当代四重奏组 The High Kings 录制的任何歌曲。该乐队的所有四名成员都是多乐器演奏家，拥有令人难以置信的独特声音，以某种方式无缝地融入四声部和声。他们自 2008 年以来一直在创作音乐，他们的专长是通过忠实于原始精髓的现代编曲，将经典的爱尔兰吉格舞和民谣带给新的听众。当我不写作时，我的副业爱好是作曲、唱歌和录制犹太音乐，我的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://bit.ly/azyashir">第一张专辑</a>深受这种方法的影响，将传统的安息日歌曲与现代旋律和乐器结合起来。<br><br><b>我会读任何作品的作家：</b>石黑一雄，既因为他的写作毫不费力地优雅，也因为它奖励对道德主题的更深入思考。举个例子：我最近读了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-buried-giant-kazuo-ishiguro/9780307455796?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《被掩埋的巨人》</i></a> ，它让我进入了另一本书《 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/forgiveness-an-alternative-account-matthew-ichihashi-potts/9780300259858?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>宽恕》</i></a> ，作者是哈佛大学纪念教堂的首席牧师马修·市桥·波茨（Matthew Ichihashi Potts），他使用了几部文学作品（包括石黑一雄的作品）来挑战传统观念宽恕并提供替代方法。 <b>[相关</b>： <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/63399d48fb1fdd0036293c1e/yom-kippur-forgiveness-anti-semitism-antepli/">我最喜欢的反犹太主义者教给我关于宽恕的知识</a><b>]</b><br><br><b>我上一次关于文化的辩论：</b>今年早些时候，我在佛罗里达州的近 1000 人面前就政治和文化中的反犹太主义问题与保守派评论员本·夏皮罗 (Ben Shapiro)<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gh6CYPboQjg">进行了辩论</a>。我们解决了从 Ye 到 Joe Rogan 的所有问题，并且几乎创造了每分钟说出最多单词的世界纪录。 （我成为一名记者的原因之一是人们可以按照自己的速度阅读我的内容，而这在现场听我讲话时是不可能的。）<br><br><b>我回到一首诗或诗行：</b> “把你的面包撒在水面上，因为多日之后，你就会找到它”（传道书 11:1）。有时，写看似无情的社会力量和不公正现象可能会让人感到徒劳。但我发现你永远不知道你的话语会在哪里被听到，以及它们最终会产生什么影响。<br><br><strong>未来一周</strong><br><br><li>安·帕切特 (Ann Patchett) 的新小说《汤姆·莱克》( <a href="https://tertulia.com/book/tom-lake-ann-patchett/9780063327528?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>Tom Lake</i></a> ) 探讨了父母在孩子出生前的浪漫史（周二发售）。</li><li>斯特林·哈乔 (Sterlin Harjo) 和塔伊卡·维迪蒂 (Taika Waititi) 创作的喜剧系列<a href="https://www.fxnetworks.com/shows/reservation-dogs"><i>《保留地狗》</i></a>第三季也是最后一季将于周三首播（在 Hulu 上播出）。</li><li>由成龙和塞斯·罗根配音的<a href="https://www.teenagemutantninjaturtlesmovie.com/?gclid=CjwKCAjwzo2mBhAUEiwAf7wjkq5qsml1R5NNWLU67VThcivgiM04HN5SbJI3XqiO_gJTBrbqlNhRyRoCJ0MQAvD_BwE"><i>《忍者神龟：突变混乱》</i></a> （周三上映）<i> </i></li><strong>散文</strong><br><br>美国家庭生活不应该如此动荡<br><br><em>艾略特·哈斯佩尔</em><br><br><p>为人父母总是充满不可预测性：凌晨两点醒来，学校打来电话，那些让<i>我胃痛的</i>可怕话语。这种日常差异通常源于生病或受惊的孩子，并且是家庭生活基本动态的一部分。然而，今天的美国父母也面临着日益严重的外部干扰和旨在提供稳定的机构的退化。其结果是，许多家庭经常会因为一些问题而陷入困境，这些问题不仅仅是不方便，但还不是灾难性的。这会滋生父母的压力、不安全感和疲惫。简而言之，美国人已经进入了一个颤抖的时代。</p><p>过去半个世纪以来，这个国家一直在走这条道路。从 20 世纪 70 年代开始，一系列经济和社会政策决策导致了政治学家雅各布·哈克 (Jacob Hacker) 所说的从政府和企业到家庭的<a href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-great-risk-shift-the-new-economic-insecurity-and-the-decline-of-the-american-dream-jacob-s-hacker/9780190844141?affiliate_id=atl-347">“巨大风险转移”</a> 。</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/parenting-challenges-american-families-child-care/674839/">阅读全文。</a><br><br><strong>更多文化内容</strong><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-richard-rhodes-interview/674828/">奥本海默专家观察<i>奥本海默</i>。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-greta-gerwig-interview/674817/">格蕾塔·葛韦格在《芭比乐园》中的课程</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/new-york-picking-up-dog-poop/674825/">什么样的恶棍不清理他们的狗？</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/lifelong-learning-new-skill-book-recommendations/674807/">终身学习者的七本书</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/the-jewish-catalog-50th-anniversary/674846/">当犹太教走向点菜时</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbenheimer-movie-theaters-hollywood-strikes/674822/">好莱坞的<i>巴本海默</i>失手</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/evolution-liars-of-nature-lixing-sun-review/674808/">大自然会说谎吗？</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/a-poem-by-janelle-tan-claude-glass-as-night-song/674800/">诗：《克劳德·格拉斯作为夜歌》</a></li><strong>赶上<em>大西洋</em></strong><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/07/chronic-fatigue-long-covid-symptoms/674834/">疲劳会击垮一个人。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/podcasts/archive/2023/07/are-you-plagued-by-the-feeling-that-everyone-used-to-be-nicer/674838/">你是否因为每个人都曾经变得更好的感觉而困扰？</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/alabama-defies-voting-rights-act-supreme-court/674850/">阿拉巴马州在投票权问题上藐视最高法院。</a></li><strong>相片集</strong><br><br>澳大利亚女足世界杯、巴黎 Lollapalooza 艺术节的表演，以及编辑精选的本周<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/photo/2023/07/photos-of-the-week-feathered-gorilla-breaching-whale-alphorn-festival/674853/">最佳照片</a>中的更多内容<br><br><i data-stringify-type="italic">Katherine Hu为本期通讯做出了贡献。</i><br><br> <em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://link.theatlantic.com/click/29767897.0/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYXRsYW50aWMuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLz91dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249YXRsYW50aWMtZGFpbHktbmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fY29udGVudD0yMDIyMTEyMQ/61813432e16c7128e42f4628B52865c35">探索我们所有的时事通讯。</a></em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/babylon-5-serialized-tv-show-recommendations/674861/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/babylon-5-serialized-tv-show-recommendations/674861/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Weird, Fragmented World of Social Media After Twitter]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>埃隆·马斯克摧毁的公共论坛永远不会被取代——没关系。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/hQLqXeptJBp-yYoePJjV8bbbp_k=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/after_twitter/original.jpg" alt="一只蓝色的鸟在飞离巢穴时掉落羽毛" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋月刊插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure><span class="smallcaps">你在蓝天吗</span>？老实说：可能不是。 Twitter 的克隆版仍处于测试阶段，并且其邀请码一直是出了名的吝啬。它的规模很小，这意味着每次新用户涌入时，现有的用户群都会感到恐慌，用算法策划的“发现”选项卡充满了令人难以置信的过度抱怨。最近一篇引起广泛讨论的帖子感叹，“蓝天长者”——在这里我应该指出，这是一项在二月份才推出移动版本的服务——由于所有的攻击而遭受着降级的体验。这句话已经成为一个即时模因。<br><br>关于 Bluesky，您只需要了解两件事。首先，它的用户正试图让<em>“skeeting”</em>一词成为现实，尽管它是比 Mastodon 的<em>“tooting”</em>更糟糕的<em>推文</em>替代方案。第二是它始终处于高度情绪化状态。现在，滚动 Twitter 的“为你”选项卡就像在装满业余种族科学家和罗马雕像化身的碗里捞苹果，哀叹我们不再建造大教堂，而 Bluesky 的类似内容则讨论了向网站开发者发送死亡威胁是否合理。如果他们真的、真的值得的话，这是可以接受的。<br><br>据我所知，Bluesky 正在吸走 Twitter 上情绪最失调的用户和最忠实的垃圾发布者。我不敢在那里发帖——根据追踪服务，我的账户曾一度是该应用程序上<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://wolfgang.raios.xyz/top_blocked">被封锁最多的</a>账户——但很高兴看到一个小而紧密、政治上独特的社区已经形成，尽管围绕着包括仇恨在内的共同利益我。尽管 Bluesky 的规模只是大型社交网络的一小部分，但它似乎已经达到了维持自身所需的临界质量，这表明埃隆·马斯克在 Twitter 上的行为已经无可挽回地破坏了该服务。无论从字面上还是隐喻上来说，我们现在都生活在后推特时代。马斯克重塑品牌后， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-musk-x-rebrand/674818/"><em>X</em></a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-musk-x-rebrand/674818/">标志着很多人不再愿意去的地方</a>。<br><br>直到最近，我还怀疑即使是像马斯克这样草率、反复无常的老板也能打垮 Twitter。留在那里的自恋者和瘾君子会让藤壶相形见绌。该网站一直比 Facebook 小得多，它之所以重要只是因为政客、记者和目前被认为是公共知识分子的人都在使用它。无论您阅读<em>《</em><em>纽约时报》</em>还是观看福克斯新闻，您都会遇到源自 Twitter 的内容。当推特将唐纳德·特朗普踢出局时，这严重削弱了他破坏新闻议程的能力，因为记者根本不准备加入这位前总统本人控制的右翼平台“真相社会”。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/05/social-media-democracy-trust-babel/629369/">摘自2022年5月号：为什么过去10年美国人的生活特别愚蠢</a><br><br>不过现在，我可以看到后 Twitter 世界的第一缕曙光。怪人、早期采用者、垃圾海报、毛茸茸的人和责骂者正在尝试 Bluesky，在那里他们可以抱怨“Elmo”和他负责“鸟类网站”的任期。真正的年轻人都在使用 TikTok。真正的婴儿潮一代从未在 Twitter 上出现过，但仍然很高兴<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/10/facebook-midlife-crisis-boomerbook/620307/">在 Facebook 上发布</a>有关 UFO 和 Bunco 之夜的内容。一些心怀不满的推特用户尝试了 Post 和 Mastodon，但第一个是墓地，第二个是非技术用户的障碍训练场。普通人和品牌转向 Instagram 的新 Threads 应用程序，然后许多普通人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://uk.pcmag.com/social-media/147939/yikes-threads-user-traffic-falls-74-from-initial-high">立即离开</a>，因为 Threads 太无聊了，没有足够的怪人、毛茸茸的人或责骂来添加调味品。 （企业可能喜欢将广告放在无可争议的励志内容旁边，但累积的效果是让 Threads 就像观看完全由电视广告组成的电视频道一样。） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i9rVcCR5IQE">Grindfluencers</a> - 听 15 分钟<em>《魔鬼经济学</em>》和<em>《艺术》</em>摘要的人<em>of War——</em>一直在 LinkedIn 上最开心，发布他们的播客内容并祝贺你的“工作周年纪念日”，这不是也永远不会是真实的事情。 Instagram 上仍然充满了感到#blessed 的性感人士，并热衷于穿着比基尼在无边泳池边摆​​姿势来展示这种谦逊。 （如果这些海报上有一个性感的妹妹，她也可以穿比基尼，然后他们就可以观察到#familyiseverything。） Twitter 现在是那些知道<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://unherd.com/thepost/did-the-desantis-campaign-know-it-was-using-a-nazi-symbol/">Sonnenrad</a>是什么并且相信它已经成为人们的首选社交网络。受到不公正的诽谤。<br><br>有些人会在考虑了上述所有选项后，最终决定接触草地。<br><br>社交媒体早期<span class="smallcaps">的许多争议都</span>源于这样的假设：用户在跨平台上拥有单一、一致的身份。研究人员达纳·博伊德和爱丽丝·马威克将由此产生的不和谐<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/dec/31/web-concepts-need-understand-2015-guide-netiquette">描述</a>为“语境崩溃”：用户在 Twitter 或 Facebook 上潜在的无限受众面前，像在私人房间里一样随意发言，招致批评。很多时候，两个亲密朋友之间本可以致命的笑话在<em>BuzzFeed</em>列表文章或电视新闻 chyron 中却遭到更广泛的反对。现在我们已经更擅长在不同的空间将自己分类为不同的模式，以至于我看到人们感叹他们在 Instagram 上知道自己是谁，在 Twitter 上知道自己是谁，<em>但我不知道自己是谁在线程上</em>。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-threads-new-suggested-rules/674709/">Yair Rosenberg：如何挽救社交媒体</a><br><br>考虑到这一趋势，令人惊讶的不是 Twitter 现在已经分裂，而是它持续了这么久。多年来，这里一直是角斗士和狮子自愿加入的竞技场。 Twitter 允许对库进行恶意攻击，也允许库针对规模稍小的库发起取消活动。<br><br>那健康吗？很长一段时间，我都担心 Upworthy 联合创始人 Eli Pariser 所说的“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ted.com/talks/eli_pariser_beware_online_filter_bubbles?language=en">过滤气泡</a>”的扩散，他将其定义为“你生活在网上的个人的、独特的信息宇宙”。我想，也许两极分化是由于我们被囚禁在回音室中而导致的，而我们正在屈服于多元化的无知——缺乏对多数观点的认识。现在我想知道过去十年的社交媒体是否让我们在另一个方向上走得太远，花太多时间与与我们不同的人在一起，以夸大我们差异的方式聚集在一起。<br><br> 2018 年，理性主义博主斯科特·亚历山大 (Scott Alexander) 发表了一篇名为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://slatestarcodex.com/2018/10/30/sort-by-controversial/">按争议排序</a>”的短篇小说。其中，一名科技初创公司的员工发明了一个程序，可以输出“剪刀声明”——立即将群体分成两半的断言。世界避免陷入无休无止的低级战争，只是因为她不小心创造了一份剪刀声明，在公司工作完成之前将公司撕裂。这个故事抓住了社交媒体作为对阳光下每个主题进行滚动公投的感觉。您是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://eu.usatoday.com/story/travel/columnist/2023/05/26/can-i-recline-my-seat-on-a-plane/70253628007/">飞机座椅</a>躺椅吗？如果来访的孩子在您家呆到很晚，您必须为他们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2022/06/04/1103075936/-swedengate-alleges-the-swedes-dont-feed-other-peoples-children-on-playdates">提供</a>晚餐吗？ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.buzzfeed.com/catesish/help-am-i-going-insane-its-definitely-blue">这件衣服</a>是蓝色的还是白色的？在政治辩论中，这意味着被迫灌输政治对手最令人头疼的痴迷。以 Twitter 账户 Libs of TikTok 为例，该账户的存在纯粹是为了从一个社交网络收集超前卫的观点，并将其提供给另一个社交网络作为愤怒的诱饵。它的流行让我认为过滤气泡，至少以温和的形式，可能不是一个坏主意。<br><br>为了蓬勃发展，社区需要界限和规范，甚至，上帝保佑我们，长辈。这就是为什么我喜欢把鼻子伸进 Bluesky 并时常深吸一口气。对于那些对动漫生殖器和有关米奇·麦康奈尔的残酷笑话都感兴趣的人们来说，这是一个有围墙的花园。他们在那里很开心。你可能不会。没关系。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 30 Jul 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-alternatives-bluesky-mastodon-threads/674859/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-alternatives-bluesky-mastodon-threads/674859/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[One More COVID Summer?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>年中浪潮可能正在连续第四年酝酿。会一直这样吗？ <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/ho_TtxSm1W41SD_VW5hNZB-_8Eo=/1x0:965x542/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/SummerCovid2/original.gif" alt="冠状病毒粒子的动画，太阳和云在其内部移动" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>保罗·斯佩拉/大西洋月刊；资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>自疫情爆发初期以来，流行病学家就一直在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2021/11/covid-seasonal-winter/620766/">等待</a>冠状病毒最终摆脱泛季节狂潮。不会再有像 2020 年第一波袭击美国那样的春季浪潮，也不会再有像当年掀起热疫苗夏季浪潮的年中浪潮。最终，或者说希望落空了，SARS-CoV-2将遵循许多其他呼吸道病原体所遵循的相同日历，至少在全球温带地区：一个严酷的冬季高峰，然后是一个休假的夏季。<br><br>但疫情爆发已经三年半了，冠状病毒仍然顽固地拒绝让最温暖的月份休息一下。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://yourlocalepidemiologist.substack.com/p/covid-19-catch-up-quick">一些</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://caitlinrivers.substack.com/p/this-week-in-outbreaks-july-28-edition">公共卫生专家</a>现在担心，在经历了一段相对平静的时期后，该病毒正在掀起另一波夏季浪潮。在美国南部和东北部，<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://biobot.io/data/">废水</a>中冠状病毒的浓度几周来一直在缓慢上升，中西部和西部地区也紧随其后；检测阳性率、急诊室诊断出的 COVID-19 以及<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://covid.cdc.gov/covid-data-tracker/#maps_new-admissions-rate-county">住院人数</a>也在上升。绝对数字仍然很小，而且可能会保持这种状态。但约翰霍普金斯大学的流行病学家凯特琳·里弗斯表示，这些都是年中浪潮正在酝酿的明显早期迹象，这将使今年夏天连续第四个夏天出现明显的冠状病毒爆发。<br><br>然而，即使疫情已经蔓延到如此程度，仍然没有人能确定夏季浪潮是否是新冠病毒的永久常态，或者该病毒是否表现出可预测的季节性模式。没有任何自然法则规定冬天一定会出现呼吸道疾病，或者夏天则不会。 “我们只是不太了解是什么驱动了呼吸道感染的周期性模式，”东北大学传染病建模师萨姆·斯卡皮诺（Sam Scarpino）说。这意味着今年任何时候这种病毒都无法保证让我们有任何懈怠。<br><br>许多病原体<em>会</em>随着季节的变化而盛衰，这是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://journals.plos.org/plospathogens/article?id=10.1371/journal.ppat.1007327">无可争议的</a>。在世界温带地区，空气中的虫子在冬天会大量繁殖，但在炎热的天气里就会被抑制。与此同时，脊髓灰质炎和其他粪便传播的病原体以及淋病和其他一些性传播感染通常在夏季上升。但注意到这些趋势是一回事，另一回事是另一回事。真正理解触发因素是另一回事。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2021/11/covid-seasonal-winter/620766/">阅读：新冠病毒现在看起来确实是季节性的</a><br><br>有些疾病更容易解释：在赤道附近，寨卡病毒和基孔肯雅热等<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5963813/">蚊媒疾病</a>的浪潮往往与携带它们的昆虫依赖天气的生命周期有关；在世界温带地区，莱姆病的发病率与夏季蜱虫的活动有关。流感也有相当有力的数据支持其对冬季的偏好。这种病毒包裹在一层称为包膜的脆弱脂肪层中，通过湿滴在空气中传播。在凉爽干燥的条件下传播得最好，这种条件可能有助于保持传染性颗粒的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://journals.asm.org/doi/10.1128/mbio.03452-22">完整性</a>并在空中飞沫。<br><br>冠状病毒与流感有足够的相似之处，大多数专家预计它也会在冬季继续传播。这两种病毒都存在于敏感的皮肤中。两者都喜欢通过气溶胶移动。两者都是相对较快的进化者，往往不会产生持久的抗感染免疫力，而这些因素有利于以相当稳定的速度重复攻击人群。出于这些原因，埃默里大学病毒学家 Anice Lowen 预计 SARS-CoV-2 将继续表现出“世界温带地区明显的冬季季节性”。冬季也是我们的身体<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/10.1146/annurev-virology-012420-022445">更容易受到</a>呼吸道细菌感染的时期：寒冷、干燥的空气会干扰将微生物从鼻子和喉咙中排出的粘液的运动；干旱还会使这些通道内的细胞枯萎和死亡。由于维生素 D 供应不足，某些免疫防御系统可能会变得有些困倦。<br><br>这些都不能阻止 SARS-CoV-2 在炎热的天气中传播，即使专家们不确定该病毒为何如此容易引发夏季浪潮。许多其他微生物也可以控制它：肠道病毒、脊髓灰质炎等等。即使是鼻病毒和腺病毒这两种最常见的感冒原因，也往往会全年传播，有时会在一年中最热的月份中肆虐。 （许多科学家推测这与这些病毒相对坚固的外层有关，但原因无疑比这更复杂。）对新冠病毒夏季浪潮的一个经常吹捧的解释是，该国某些地区的人们躲在室内，以避暑。战胜炎热。但洛文告诉我，这个论点本身“是站不住脚的”。在工业化国家，人们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cpsc.gov/safety-education/safety-guides/home/indoor-air-pollution-introduction-health-professionals">90% 以上的时间都在室内度过</a>。<br><br>也就是说，许多小的影响的积累可以共同创造一个季节性的临界点。夏季<em>是</em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://aytm.com/post/vacations-survey">特别受欢迎的旅行季节</a>，经常参加大型聚会。里弗斯说，距离冬季还有好几个月，感染和疫苗接种也很多，每年的这个时候，人群免疫力也可能处于相对较低的水平。此外，尽管 SARS-CoV-2 与流感有很多相似之处，但它本身就是一种野兽：迄今为止，它对人类的影响更长期、更<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2022/12/covid-common-cold-status-differentiation/672472/">严重</a>，并且以更快的速度产生席卷人群的变种。这些动态都会影响波浪何时出现。<br><br>尽管某些身体防御能力确实会在寒冷中下降，但数据并不支持夏季免疫力单方面更强的观点。纽约“我们行动环境正义”组织的环境健康主任米凯拉·马丁内斯告诉我，情况远比这复杂。多年来，她和其他研究人员一直在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8987173/">收集</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33817568/">证据</a>，表明我们的身体具有明显的季节性免疫特征——一些防御分子在夏季出现峰值，而另一些则在冬季出现峰值。这些转变的后果尚不明显。但其中一些可以帮助解释冠状病毒何时传播。同样的道理，冬季也不是疾病肆虐的时期。瑞典卡罗林斯卡研究所的免疫学家 Xaquin Castro Dopico 发现，北半球的免疫系统<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25965853/">在冬天可能更容易发炎——</a>是的，这可能会使某些疾病发作更加严重，但也可以改善<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19889749/">反应</a>对于某些疫苗接种。<br><br>所有这些解释都可能适用于新冠病毒夏季的波动——或者也许没有一个适用。 “每个人都希望得到一个非常简单的季节性答案，”马丁内斯告诉我。但这种情况可能根本不存在。马丁内斯告诉我，即使是小儿麻痹症这种在美国被消灭之前的严重<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4474890/">夏季</a>疾病，其季节性的原因几十年来也一直是“一个悬而未决的问题”。<br><br>里弗斯希望，冠状病毒的永久模式可能已经开始显现：冬季的鼎盛时期，以及夏季可能出现的较小的驼峰。 “我们已经进入第四年了，我们年复一年地看到同样的事情，”她告诉我。但一些专家担心，讨论 COVID-19 季节性还为时过早。 SARS-CoV-2 对人类来说仍然很新鲜，其模式<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/03/kids-babies-getting-covid-exposure-vaccines/673368/">可能与最终形式相去甚远</a>。在极端情况下，研究人员在大流行最初几年观察到的模式可能根本无法预示未来，因为它们概括了如此多的变化：最初缺乏免疫力和快速获得免疫力、病毒的进化、病毒的潮起潮落。面具，等等。耶鲁大学传染病建模师布兰登·奥格布努 (Brandon Ogbunu) 表示，在这种相互抵消的影响中，“你会得到一些违反直觉的动态”，而这种动态不一定会持续很长时间。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/03/kids-babies-getting-covid-exposure-vaccines/673368/">阅读：新冠疫情的下一阶段现已开始</a><br><br><br>由于现在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.healthdata.org/sites/default/files/files/1_briefing_Global_6.pdf">世界上很多地方都</a>受到感染、接种疫苗或两者兼而有之，而且新冠疫情缓解措施几乎完全消失，全球局势现在的变化不再那么大。病毒本身虽然仍然明显以惊人的速度发生变化，但在一年半多的时间里还没有实现 Omicron 级别的进化跳跃。但目前还没有人能够保证其可预测性。疫苗接种的节奏尚未确定；东北大学的斯卡皮诺也不准备否认病毒进化意外的想法。也许夏季浪潮的发生就表明 SARS-CoV-2 仍将是四季皆宜的微生物。或者它们可能是这场大流行病的死亡之声的一部分——系统中尚未平静下来的噪音。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/summer-covid-wave-2023/674863/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/summer-covid-wave-2023/674863/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Misunderstood Reason Millions of Americans Stopped Going to Church]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>驱赶人们出走的决定性问题是……21世纪美国人的生活是如何运作的。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/SNLWHQRKMYXKJeLjdVhRTWLZR4Q=/0x312:3000x2000/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_455600083/original.jpg" alt="长凳上放着一本圣经。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>斯宾塞普拉特/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>在内布拉斯加州林肯市的童年教堂里，几乎所有和我一起长大的人都不再是基督徒了。这并不罕见。过去 25 年里，四千万美国人不再去教堂。 That&#39;s something like 12 percent of the population, and it represents the largest concentrated change in church attendance in American history. As a Christian, I feel this shift acutely. My wife and I wonder whether the institutions and communities that have helped preserve us in our own faith will still exist for our four children, let alone whatever grandkids we might one day have.<br><br> This change is also bad news for America as a whole: Participation in a religious community generally correlates with <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2016/10/28/religion-church-attendance-mortality-column/92676964/">better health outcomes and longer life</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.philanthropyroundtable.org/magazine/less-god-less-giving/">higher financial generosity</a> , and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thepublicdiscourse.com/2018/03/20935/">more stable families</a> —all of which are desperately needed in a nation with rising rates of loneliness, mental illness, and alcohol and drug dependency.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/02/christianity-secularization-america-renewal-modernity/672948/">Timothy Keller: American Christianity is due for a revival</a><br><br> A new book, written by Jim Davis, a pastor at an evangelical church in Orlando, and Michael Graham, a writer with the Gospel Coalition, draws on surveys of more than 7,000 Americans by the political scientists Ryan Burge and Paul Djupe, attempting to explain why people have left churches—or “dechurched,” in the book&#39;s lingo—and what, if anything, can be done to get some people to come back. The book raises an intriguing possibility: What if the problem isn&#39;t that churches are asking too much of their members, but that they aren&#39;t asking nearly enough?<br><br> <i>The Great Dechurching</i> finds that religious abuse and more general moral corruption in churches have driven people away. This is, of course, an indictment of the failures of many leaders who did not address abuse in their church. But Davis and Graham also find that a much larger share of those who have left church have done so for more banal reasons. The book suggests that the defining problem driving out most people who leave is … just how American life works in the 21st century. Contemporary America simply isn&#39;t set up to promote mutuality, care, or common life. Rather, it is designed to maximize individual accomplishment as defined by professional and financial success. Such a system leaves precious little time or energy for forms of community that don&#39;t contribute to one&#39;s own professional life or, as one ages, the professional prospects of one&#39;s children. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/02/religion-workism-making-americans-miserable/583441/">Workism</a> reigns in America, and because of it, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hhs.gov/about/news/2023/05/03/new-surgeon-general-advisory-raises-alarm-about-devastating-impact-epidemic-loneliness-isolation-united-states.html">community in America</a> , religious community included, is a math problem that doesn&#39;t add up.<br><br> Numerous victims of abuse in church environments can identify a moment when they lost the ability to believe, when they almost felt their faith draining out of them. The book shows, though, that for most Americans who were once a part of churches but have since left, the process of leaving was gradual, and in many cases they didn&#39;t realize it was even happening until it already had. It&#39;s less like jumping off a cliff and more like driving down a slope, eventually realizing that you can no longer see the place you started from.<br><br> Consider one of the composite characters that Graham and Davis use in the book to describe a typical evangelical dechurcher: a 30-something woman who grew up in a suburban megachurch, was heavily invested in a campus ministry while in college, then after graduating moved into a full-time job and began attending a young-adults group in a local church. In her 20s, she meets a guy who is less religiously engaged, they get married, and, at some point early in their marriage, after their first or second child is born, they stop going to church. Maybe the baby isn&#39;t sleeping well and when Sunday morning comes around, it is simply easier to stay home and catch whatever sleep is available as the baby (finally) falls asleep.<br><br> In other cases, a person might be entering mid-career, working a high-stress job requiring a 60- or 70-hour workweek. Add to that 15 hours of commute time, and suddenly something like two-thirds of their waking hours in the week are already accounted for. And so when a friend invites them to a Sunday-morning brunch, they probably want to go to church, but they also want to see that friend, because they haven&#39;t been able to see them for months. The friend wins out.<br><br> After a few weeks of either scenario, the thought of going to church on Sunday carries a certain mental burden with it—you might <i>want</i> to go, but you also dread the inevitable questions about where you have been. “I skipped church to go to brunch with a friend” or “I was just too tired to come” don&#39;t sound like convincing excuses as you rehearse the conversation in your mind. Soon it actually sounds like it&#39;d be harder to attend than to skip, even if some part of you still wants to go. The underlying challenge for many is that their lives are stretched like a rubber band about to snap—and church attendance ends up feeling like an item on a checklist that&#39;s already too long.<br><br> What can churches do in such a context? In theory, the Christian Church could be an antidote to all that. What is more needed in our time than a community marked by sincere love, sharing what they have from each according to their ability and to each according to their need, eating together regularly, generously serving neighbors, and living lives of quiet virtue and prayer? A healthy church can be a safety net in the harsh American economy by offering its members material assistance in times of need: meals after a baby is born, money for rent after a layoff. Perhaps more important, it reminds people that their identity is not in their job or how much money they make; they are children of God, loved and protected and infinitely valuable.<br><br> But a vibrant, life-giving church requires more, not less, time and energy from its members. It asks people to prioritize one another over our career, to prioritize prayer and time reading scripture over accomplishment. This may seem like a tough sell in an era of dechurching. If people are already leaving—especially if they are leaving because they feel too busy and burned out to attend church regularly—why would they want to be part of a church that asks so much of them?<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/01/us-religious-affiliation-rates-declining/672729/">Read: American religion is not dead yet</a><br><br> Although understandable, that isn&#39;t quite the right question. The problem in front of us is not that we have a healthy, sustainable society that doesn&#39;t have room for church. The problem is that many Americans have adopted a way of life that has left us lonely, anxious, and uncertain of how to live in community with other people.<br><br> The tragedy of American churches is that they have been so caught up in this same world that we now find they have nothing to offer these suffering people that can&#39;t be more easily found somewhere else. American churches have too often been content to function as a kind of vaguely spiritual NGO, an organization of detached individuals who meet together for religious services that inspire them, provide practical life advice, or offer positive emotional experiences. Too often it has not been a community that through its preaching and living bears witness to another way to live.<br><br> The theologian Stanley Hauerwas <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.christiancentury.org/article/interview/dangers-providing-pastoral-care">captured the problem well</a> when he said that “pastoral care has become obsessed with the personal wounds of people in advanced industrial societies who have discovered that their lives lack meaning.” The difficulty is that many of the wounds and aches provoked by our current order aren&#39;t of a sort that can be managed or life-hacked away. They are resolved only by changing one&#39;s life, by becoming a radically different sort of person belonging to a radically different sort of community.<br><br> Last fall, I spent several days in New York City, during which time I visited a home owned by <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bruderhof.com/">a group of pacifist Christians</a> that lives from a common purse—meaning the members do not have privately held property but share their property and money. Their simple life and shared finances allow their schedules to be more flexible, making for a thicker immediate community and greater generosity to neighbors, as well as a richer life of prayer and private devotion to God, all supported by a deep commitment to their church.<br><br> This is, admittedly, an extreme example. But this community was thriving not because it found ways to scale down what it asked of its members but because it found a way to scale up what they provided to one another. Their way of living frees them from the treadmill of workism. Work, in this community, is judged not by the money it generates but by the people it serves. In a workist culture that believes <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://mereorthodoxy.com/dignity-beyond-accomplishment">dignity is grounded in accomplishment</a> , simply reclaiming this alternative form of dignity becomes a radical act.<br><br> In the Gospels, Jesus tells his first disciples to leave their old way of life behind, going so far as abandoning their plow or fishing nets where they are and, if necessary, even leaving behind their parents. A church that doesn&#39;t expect at least this much from one another isn&#39;t really a church in the way Jesus spoke about it. If Graham and Davis are right, it also is likely a church that won&#39;t survive the challenges facing us today.<br><br> The great dechurching could be the beginning of a new moment for churches, a moment marked less by aspiration to respectability and success, with less focus on individuals aligning themselves with American values and assumptions. We could be a witness to another way of life outside conventionally American measures of success. Churches could model better, truer sorts of communities, ones in which the hungry are fed, the weak are lifted up, and the proud are cast down. Such communities might not have the money, success, and influence that many American churches have so often pursued in recent years. But if such communities look less like those churches, they might also look more like the sorts of communities Jesus expected his followers to create.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Jul 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/christian-church-communitiy-participation-drop/674843/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/christian-church-communitiy-participation-drop/674843/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Why the Studios Are Risking Everything]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> An extended strike could kill off movie theaters. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/QPwGjAj5qgmmN-Hh5jMJnG-Ca40=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/studios_strike/original.jpg" alt="空荡荡的电影院和空白屏幕的插图" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Millennium Images / Gallery Stock</figcaption></figure> Labor stoppages are, first and foremost, about money, and the concurrent Screen Actors Guild and Writers Guild of America strikes are no exception. The actors and the writers want more of it, as well as limits on the use of AI. The studios say they don&#39;t have nearly as much to distribute as the actors and the writers would like given the massive expenses they&#39;ve incurred while standing up their streaming services. They find themselves at an impasse that threatens to reduce the overall pot even further by putting in jeopardy one of the industry&#39;s greatest assets: movie theaters.<br><br> Hollywood has a history of treating evolving consumer habits first as a threat to theatrical dollars and then as a tool to be co-opted in the pursuit of earning ever-greater profits. Studios were first hesitant to license their films to television networks and then realized the small screen was an untapped market. Hollywood fought tooth and nail against VHS—fearing both illegal piracy and customers legally taping the movies that studios had licensed to TV and cable networks—until it realized home-video rentals and sales were a gold mine. VHS&#39;s successor, DVD, peaked at <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/08/the-death-of-the-dvd-why-sales-dropped-more-than-86percent-in-13-years.html">$16.3 billion in annual sales in 2005</a> , or nearly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.boxofficemojo.com/year/?ref_=bo_nb_yld_secondarytab">two times the domestic box office</a> , before declining in the face of streaming. In some ways, theatrical became almost a loss leader for home-video sales; <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gF6K2IxC9O8">as Matt Damon has said</a> , home-video sales helped prop up virtually the whole marketplace for “the kinds of movies that I loved,” movies for adults.<br><br> The birth of streaming—specifically, the rise of Netflix&#39;s online component—coincided with a decline in DVD sales that created an opportunity for Netflix&#39;s honchos. “Once it added new ways for viewers to watch movies and TV shows [online] from the couch in their living rooms … subscriptions skyrocketed 63 percent,” Dade Hayes and Dawn Chmielewski write in their book, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/binge-times-inside-hollywood-s-furious-billion-dollar-battle-to-take-down-netflix-dade-hayes/9780062980007?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>Binge Times: Inside Hollywood&#39;s Furious Billion-Dollar Battle to Take Down Netflix</em></a> <em>.</em> “The budding streaming service grew at Hollywood&#39;s expense. [The CEO Reed] Hastings and company deftly exploited the studios&#39; compensation structure, which paid rich bonuses when executive hit their financial targets.”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/writers-strike-hollywood-wga-union-streaming-platforms/674056/">Gavin Mueller: The luddites of Hollywood</a><br><br> Its first-mover advantage, enormous movie libraries acquired from shortsighted Hollywood execs, and buzzy original series such as <em>House of Cards</em> , <em>Orange Is the New Black</em> , and <em>Stranger Things</em> helped Netflix become a company that could generate <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.yahoo.com/now/netflix-full-2022-earnings-eps-121625446.html">more than $31 billion in revenue worldwide last year</a> , roughly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2020/film/box-office/box-office-us-misses-record-disney-dominates-1203453752/">three-quarters the size of the combined take at the worldwide box office</a> of every movie studio in 2019, the last pre-COVID year. It&#39;s why the company has a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NFLX">market cap</a> of $190 billion or so.<br><br> The studios and their corporate overlords look at Netflix&#39;s stock price and revenues and wonder why they can&#39;t print money too. This is why the studios were all planning their own jumps to streaming even before the pandemic began. After the pandemic started, they jumped in feet first—and promptly found themselves drowning.<br><br> As Matthew Ball notes in his <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thestreamingbook.com/">authoritative look at the streaming wars so far</a> , studios&#39; move to streaming has been fraught and results have been mixed. Consider NBCUniversal&#39;s entrant in the contest, Peacock, which is tentatively on track to hit both subscriber and revenue numbers yet is still hemorrhaging cash. “Comcast had originally said that from 2020 through 2024, Peacock would never lose more than $1B in a single year, cumulative losses would peak at $2B, and breakeven would be achieved in 2024. Yet Peacock lost $663MM in 2020, $1.7B in 2021, and $2.5B in 2022. Cumulative losses now exceed $5B,” Ball <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thestreamingbook.com/chapters/three-years-into-hollywoods-five-year-plan">writes</a> . Aside from those about Netflix, most positive headlines about streaming services <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/05/disney-plus-loses-subscribers-streaming-quarter-bob-iger-1235362109/">boil down to</a> “Well, They Lost a Little Less This Quarter Than Analysts Thought They Would.”<br><br> The issue for most of these companies isn&#39;t revenue; it&#39;s spending. Until recently, more money was being spent on more television shows and movies than ever before; as the Motion Picture Association noted in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.motionpictures.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/MPA-2021-THEME-Report-FINAL.pdf">its 2021 report</a> on the state of showbiz, 1,826 original series were produced across streaming, cable, and broadcast in 2021. The number of television shows released on streaming channels roughly doubled from 2019 to 2021.<br><br> The studios looked at this and said, “More writers and more actors are getting more work. What else do you want from us?” As the screenwriter Zack Stentz <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/04/30/opinion/hollywood-writers-guild-strike.html">noted</a> in <em>The New York Times</em> , the number of WGA members reporting earnings “during the streaming-driven boom years” bumped up “from 4,500 to more than 6,000.” And the WGA reported collecting more fees than ever before in 2022, which the anonymous streaming insider Entertainment Strategy Guy suggests means that it&#39;s <em>likely</em> that WGA writers collected <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://entertainmentstrategyguy.com/2023/07/20/exclusive-wga-screenwriter-earnings-likely-broke-records-in-2022/">more total pay than ever before</a> . This is one reason why Disney&#39;s CEO, Bob Iger, feels comfortable going <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2023/tv/news/bob-iger-writers-actors-strike-disney-ceo-1235669169/">on TV saying</a> writers and actors are being unrealistic, arguing that “they are adding to the set of the challenges that this business is already facing that is, quite frankly, very disruptive.”<br><br> That disruption is upon us as studios have begun to take movies off the release calendar. <em>Challengers</em> , the Zendaya-led MGM picture in the new genre of “tennis threesome movie,” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2023/film/global/challengers-zendaya-skips-venice-film-festival-sag-aftra-strike-1235672841/">had been set to open this year&#39;s Venice film festival</a> ; it has been pushed back to 2024 in the hopes that the actor will be available to walk the red carpet then. Searchlight Pictures is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/07/searchlights-poor-things-emma-stone-september-december-1235447551/">pushing</a> the new Yorgos Lanthimos picture, <em>Poor Things</em> , back from September to December. Ethan Coen&#39;s <em>Drive-Away Dolls</em> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/07/dune-part-two-drive-away-dolls-actors-strike-box-office-1235448062/">might miss the fall festival circuit</a> . A24 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/07/a24-problemista-actors-strike-wga-strike-1235444874/">also pulled <em>Problemista</em> from its August release date</a> . And Warner Bros. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2023/07/dune-part-two-may-be-delayed-thanks-to-hollywoods-strikes#:~:text=Dune%3A%20Part%20Two%2C%20director%20Denis,of%20discussions%20told%20the%20outlet.">might just</a> pull <em>Dune: Part Two</em> from its November release date. That would leave the box office relatively barren.<br><br> As someone who spent all of 2020 watching studios repeatedly push movies back three (or six, or nine) months in the hopes of releasing after the pandemic had abated, I&#39;m sorry to say that this is starting to feel suspiciously like COVID Redux. To be clear, pushing release dates is a totally logical move on the part of the studios as long as the strike persists: No stars means no promo. But I worry that a paucity of movies in theaters so hot on the heels of a previous extended absence of movies in theaters could mean no more theaters, period.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/05/hollywood-writers-strike-wga/673926/">Read: Why you should pay attention to the Hollywood writer&#39;s strike</a><br><br> This is, perhaps, hyperbole, but only slightly. The number of screens in the United States <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movies/movie-news/movie-theater-screen-losses-ticket-prices-1235346523/">declined by 5 percent</a> during pandemic shutdowns; the only reason the damage wasn&#39;t more severe was AMC&#39;s unlikely emergence as a meme stock in 2021, which helped the company <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.polygon.com/movies/2021/1/29/22256360/amc-stock-price-reddit-rally-robinhood-debt-conversion">pay down $600 million in debt</a> . But box-office earnings remain nearly 20 percent below 2019 and nearly 25 percent below 2018, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.boxofficemojo.com/year/ytd/">year to date</a> . Audiences were relatively understanding about pandemic-related theater closures and have started coming back, but getting them out of the moviegoing habit again just as things have been getting back on track could have dire consequences.<br><br> And these consequences would be dire for <em>everyone</em> in the industry. Theatrical releases remain the best and most consistent individual way to monetize any one movie. They&#39;re the top of the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thebulwark.com/moving-films-to-vod-cant-make-up-the-revenue-the-traditional-theatrical-model-generates/">revenue waterfall</a> for films. Although some movies (particularly low-to-mid-budget pictures) may earn more in aggregate from nontheatrical than theatrical revenue, theatrical releases are still the biggest piece of the puzzle when it comes to completing the profitability picture. Even successful experiments in home distribution <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/07/business/media/universal-premium-video-on-demand.html">like Universal&#39;s premium video-on-demand window</a> —in which the studio charges extra for big releases still in theaters—depend on the prestige bump that theatrical exhibition bestows. The theatrical release is why customers are willing to spend $20 to rent a movie.<br><br> All of which is to say that Iger is right in one very narrow sense: This is a disruptive time for the entertainment industry, and a prolonged shutdown could be disastrous, leading to less money for everyone. But the disruption, accelerated by COVID, is a direct result of the studios&#39; own desire to replicate the Netflix model and treat the load-bearing wall that is theatrical release as a decorative trifle, easily demolished to complete some garish open floor plan of the sort preferred on the home-improvement shows broadcast by Warner Bros. Discovery CEO David Zaslav&#39;s beloved HGTV.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywood-writers-actor-guild-strike/674848/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywood-writers-actor-guild-strike/674848/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[America Is Drowning in Packages]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> UPS workers have an impossible job in the Amazon age. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/V6dZ4_O0a4054tchlComWJ1bWms=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/ups_final_2/original.jpg" alt="A globe surrounded by packages" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by The Atlantic.资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure> When UPS delivery workers last went on strike, in 1997, the nature of their job was very different. Amazon, then merely an online bookstore, was barely two years out from its very first sale. Buying jeans, or new furniture, or really anything, still required most people to get in their car and head to the local mall. By the time the International Brotherhood of Teamsters announced on Tuesday that it had reached a tentative agreement with UPS that would avoid a strike and keep hundreds of thousands of union members on the job, those workers&#39; role in American life had changed fundamentally.<br><br> The new contract, which still needs to be ratified by the union&#39;s members, came not a moment too soon. UPS handles a quantity of stuff so enormous that the company estimates its workers put their hands on roughly 6 percent of the country&#39;s gross domestic product, and the company delivers nearly a quarter of all American packages. Internet retail and the volume of delivery services required to fill it have made America ever more dependent on the difficult, labor-intensive work of what&#39;s known as last-mile package delivery. The country&#39;s infrastructure and workforce are still struggling to catch up.<br><br> Even in the Amazon age, the volume of packages now delivered in the US can sound completely absurd. In 2000, the United States Postal Service—the country&#39;s biggest parcel shipper—delivered 2.4 billion packages. By 2022, that number had ballooned to 7.2 billion. UPS now handles 5.2 billion domestic packages annually, versus the 3.2 billion it handled in 2000, and Amazon&#39;s logistics operation, which did not start delivering its own packages in earnest <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-to-launch-delivery-service-that-would-vie-with-fedex-ups-1518175920">until 2018</a> , has become the country&#39;s third-largest shipper, delivering almost 5 billion (but not nearly all) of the company&#39;s packages last year. And all of these packages are going to a customer base that has been trained by retailers to expect packages to arrive in just a few days—far faster than turnaround expectations used to be.<br><br> You might only really notice the handful of packages that come to <em>your</em> home each week ( <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pitneybowes.com/content/dam/pitneybowes/us/en/shipping-index/22-pbcs-04529-2021-global-parcel-shipping-index-ebook-web-002.pdf">three to four</a> in an average household). But every single time you get one, that same day there are more than 50 million other people in the country refreshing their tracking info and checking their doorbell-camera feeds to see if their new shoes or prescription refill has arrived too. And those packages had to be loaded onto a series of trucks, driven to an address, and then carried to a welcome mat by humans.<br><br> Spraying America with a nonstop fire hose of parcels has consequences that are tough for workers and not always visible to the rest of us. More packages require <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trucks-roads-damage-traffic-supply-chain-11643210764">more trucks</a> on the road, which means more semis on the country&#39;s interstates and more oversize delivery vehicles on residential streets, worsening traffic for everyone. These vehicles put enormous stress on roads and bridges, requiring more frequent repairs. Streets built primarily for passenger cars can be too narrow or have turns too tight for even the most skilled drivers of cargo vehicles to navigate easily, and conducting so many home deliveries a year inevitably results in accidents, stuck vehicles, and injuries. These same roads tend not to have easy spots for trucks to park when it&#39;s time to actually make a delivery, so they block streets and create more traffic. And each driver has to do it over and over again, dozens of times a day, until the country&#39;s tens of millions of daily packages are delivered and each of hundreds of thousands of cargo vehicles is empty.<br><br> Once a package is off the truck, things aren&#39;t necessarily much easier. Across the country, the median age of local housing stock predates the wide adoption of online shopping, which means that most homes were built before so many of us were getting stuff delivered multiple times a week while away at work. Mailboxes are mostly still the size that they&#39;ve always been, so drivers need to chuck your stuff onto your porch or behind a bush and hope for the best. In apartment complexes, just gaining entry can be a struggle, and many older properties don&#39;t have a mail room big enough to store everything safely. Unless you live in a luxury building, you probably don&#39;t have a front desk with an attendant to accept packages in your stead. And when a bunch of brand-new, unsecured stuff is lying around, some of it is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2019/11/stealing-amazon-packages-age-nextdoor/598156/">bound to get stolen</a> , though assuming theft can be misguided: Package volume is so high and getting them all to the right place is such intricate work that a lot of missing packages were <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/02/nyregion/online-shopping-package-theft.html">simply misdelivered</a> .<br><br> And yet the size of delivery workforces at the country&#39;s major shippers has not increased at the same rate as the boom in packages and the ever-shortening customer expectations on shipping time. Many shipping companies have hired lower-paid part-time workers to fill the gaps instead of creating new full-time jobs, and a significant portion of Amazon&#39;s deliveries are made by gig workers who use their own vehicles and are paid by the package.<br><br> Gig worker or not, all of this work takes place every day of the year and mostly outside, so drivers are handling more parcels and doing more physical labor in a climate that&#39;s becoming more extreme, and they&#39;re doing it largely in cargo vehicles that lack air-conditioning. UPS drivers have <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/08/20/business/ups-postal-workers-heat-stroke-deaths.html">died on the job</a> from heat exposure, and in negotiations between the Teamsters and UPS, air-conditioning for delivery vehicles became a major sticking point. (The union&#39;s new contract, if ratified, would guarantee AC in new delivery vehicles and add better ventilation to old ones.)<br><br> Still, better pay and safety improvements are only the first steps to address the larger spectrum of issues that delivery workers face in moving around so many packages so quickly. Improvements to road and bridge safety are not sexy line items on government budgets, and the trucks will keep rolling whether those improvements are made or not. It may just be impossible to fully retrofit the delivery economy that&#39;s been foisted on Americans by tech companies into the physical reality of daily life. Shippers are going to keep trying anyway.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ups-strike-union-contract-package-deliveries/674864/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ups-strike-union-contract-package-deliveries/674864/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Big Beer Is Not So Big Anymore]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The brew was once king of all beverages, but times are changing. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/vxFqpe3t6bo7DqN25fTzEIgdeqM=/1x281:3542x2273/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_82093880/original.jpg" alt="人们围成一圈，手里拿着啤酒" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Imagno / Getty</figcaption></figure> <small><em>Updated at 6:48 pm ET on July 28, 2023</em></small><br><br><small><i data-stringify-type="italic">这是</i>《大西洋<i data-stringify-type="italic">日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">在这里注册。</a></i></small><br><br> Beer was once king. Now, with seltzers, canned cocktails, and other tasty beverages on the rise, what will become of brews?<br><br> First, here are four new stories from <i>The Atlantic</i> :<br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-ken/674852/">芭比就是一切。肯就是其他一切。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/donald-trump-indictment-jack-smith/674855/">Trump&#39;s legal turmoil just keeps getting worse.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/soda-lemon-lime-starry-sprite-pop/674857/">All soda is lemon-lime soda.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/alabama-defies-voting-rights-act-supreme-court/674850/">阿拉巴马州在投票权问题上藐视最高法院。</a></li> <strong>The Decline of the Brew</strong><br><br> It&#39;s Friday, so I&#39;ll go ahead and say it: I love cracking open a cold one. It&#39;s not just the taste of beer itself or the alcohol. For me, drinking a beer is also about the pleasure of the ritual. Indeed, so much do I enjoy cracking open cold ones that I also often drink hop water, nonalcoholic seltzers flavored with hops. (They taste good and have the added benefit of making me feel virtuous.)<br><br> On Tuesday evening, I was lying on my chaise lounge, reading a magazine and sipping a new variety of hop water, which I had nestled into a koozie emblazoned with a crab and the words <span class="smallcaps">Don&#39;t bother me I&#39;m crabby.</span> I was relaxed. So imagine my surprise when I looked at the can and discovered that the drink contained adaptogens and nootropics. I don&#39;t really know what those are; I can barely pronounce the latter. I thought I was just drinking sparkling water with a bit of flavoring! Did I feel a bit weird because I was tired, I suddenly wondered, or because there were supplements in my hop water? Would this drink <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vox.com/the-goods/2019/7/8/18772467/nootropics-silicon-valley-brain-fitness-goop-smart-drugs">make me a genius</a> ?<br><br> In recent years, canned and bottled beverages of every stripe have proliferated. Canned cocktails, hard seltzers, ciders, nonalcoholic beers, CBD drinks, and hop waters share shelf space with traditional beer. It can be hard to keep up. Changing consumer preferences, the high costs of doing business, and competitive pressure mean that the beer industry is not the retail big dog it once was. Beer once held a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pbs.org/newshour/economy/spirits-surpass-beer-for-u-s-market-share-supremacy-data-shows">hefty lead</a> in the market over other alcoholic drinks.不再。 Lester Jones, the chief economist of the National Beer Wholesalers Association, told me that the market shrank by <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.brewersassociation.org/press-releases/brewers-association-releases-annual-craft-brewing-industry-production-report-and-top-50-producing-craft-brewing-companies-for-2022/">3 percent in volume last year</a> , continuing a downward trend that began around 2000, and we&#39;re now in the midst of one of the worst years so far since beer&#39;s decline began.<br><br> Part of the reason for the contraction in beer-volume sales is that people are diversifying their alcohol consumption, adding drinks such as spirits to the rotation. Whereas beer prices have roughly tracked with inflation over the past 20 years, liquor has gotten relatively cheaper, Bart Watson, the chief economist of the Brewers Association, a craft-beer trade organization, told me. For more than a decade, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/commodity-markets-business-464e8a74c984d1acd65d81ac6df17c52">spirits</a> have been gaining market share. Demographic shifts also tell part of the story: The <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/22/us/census-median-age.html">American population is older</a> than ever before. As Boomers age into retirement and Millennials enter their 40s, they are reaching for different drinks for different types of occasions. A retiree might enjoy an expensive bottle of wine with dinner, and a Millennial might mix cocktails for a birthday celebration. (Or, if you&#39;re me, you might break out a hop water while chilling.)<br><br> The next generation is not waiting in the wings to replace them. Young people “are just drinking less beer,” Watson said, and many seem to be buying <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/claraludmir/2023/06/27/why-genz-is-drinking-less-and-what-this-means-for-the-alcohol-industry/">less alcohol</a> , in general. Those who <i>are</i> drinking have a panoply of options to choose from. No longer are college kids just guzzling Natty Light and slapping bags of Franzia. Now young people are turning 21 and entering a market filled with relatively affordable seltzers, canned cocktails, and ciders—not to mention EANABs, the name my college dorm used to describe Equally Attractive Nonalcoholic Beverages.<br><br> For those who do still drink beer, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://slate.com/business/2023/07/beer-sales-decline-explained-hard-seltzer-craft-beer.html">preferences are shifting</a> in how <i>much</i> beer they want to buy and what kind. “People are drinking less beer, but they are drinking higher-priced beer,” Jones explained, as some mass-produced beers have gotten more expensive, and pricier craft beer now occupies more of the market. Premium light beers have been losing market share for years, Watson told me.<br><br> Then, this spring, light beer got an unwelcome turn in the spotlight when a right-wing campaign to cancel Bud Light <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rise-and-fall-bud-light-boycott/674752/">picked up steam</a> . Consumers boycotted the beer after Dylan Mulvaney, a transgender influencer, posted a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/article/bud-light-boycott.html">promotional video</a> for the brand on Instagram. In June, after 20 years as <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rise-and-fall-bud-light-boycott/674752/">America&#39;s best-selling beer</a> , Bud Light was <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/23/business/modelo-bud-light.html">surpassed by Modelo</a> . That was not totally unexpected—“it was a question of when, not if” Modelo would reach the top, Watson told me, though the backlash accelerated the trend. For years, Modelo had been on track to surpass Bud Light as <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/23/business/modelo-bud-light.html">consumers began gravitating</a> toward more expensive, imported beers.<br><br> In the aftermath of the backlash, two Bud Light executives went <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-bud-light-handled-an-uproar-over-a-promotion-with-a-transgender-advocate-e457d5c6?mod=hp_lead_pos11">on leave</a> . As it happens, I interviewed one of them, Alissa Heinerscheid, last January, before all of this happened. In her capacity as vice president of marketing for Bud Light, Heinerscheid <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/02/10/business/media/beer-ads-super-bowl.html">told me at the time that</a> the brand&#39;s 2023 Super Bowl ad, featuring a breezy scene of a couple dancing while drinking the beer, was going for a “lighter and brighter” energy than in years past (notable past ads include Budweiser&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thedrum.com/news/2022/06/14/world-s-best-ads-ever-15-budweiser-simply-asks-wassup">“Wasssuuuup”</a> and Bud Light&#39;s original party animal, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/09/magazine/letter-of-recommendation-spuds-mackenzie.html">Spuds MacKenzie</a> ). A couple of months later, on a podcast, she discussed her interest in reaching new audiences and making the brand&#39;s image less “fratty” in hopes of turning around a brand in decline. In trying to carry out that mission to engage new customers, she met an audience—or at least a vocal portion of it—that was unwilling to accept changes that would make the brand more inclusive. (Asked for comment, Anheuser-Busch, the parent company of Bud Light, sent a statement from Bud Light&#39;s current vice president of marketing, Todd Allen, emphasizing that “people want us to get back to what we do best: being the beer of easy enjoyment.” The brand&#39;s current strategy, he said, “is really about reaffirming the role that Bud Light plays in people&#39;s lives.” An Anheuser-Busch spokesperson added that Bud Light remains the top beer brand in the US in 2023.)<br><br> The beverage sector will likely keep changing—or at least keep trying to change—to meet the moment. For many alcohol brands, that could look like adding seltzers and other canned delicacies to the mix. Anheuser-Busch now owns seltzer, canned-cocktail, and hard-tea brands. And in 2020, Molson Coors Brewing Company undertook a telling rebrand: It&#39;s now called Molson Coors Beverage Company.<br><br> <b>Related:</b><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rise-and-fall-bud-light-boycott/674752/">The real mystery of Bud Light</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2022/07/white-claw-hard-seltzer-tastes-bad/670492/">Hard seltzer has gone flat.</a></li> <strong>Today&#39;s News</strong><br><br><li> New charges <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/28/politics/trump-classified-documents-case-2024/index.html">were brought</a> against former President Donald Trump and two of his associates, in an expansion of the Mar-a-Lago classified-documents case.</li><li> President Joe Biden signed a <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/28/us/politics/biden-military-sexual-assault.html">significant executive order</a> altering the military legal system, ensuring that special prosecutors outside of the chain of command—as opposed to commanders—will decide whether to pursue charges in cases of sexual assault, rape, and murder.</li><li> Nearly <a href="https://apnews.com/article/heat-floods-climate-environment-storm-weather-31d075a9357730ea3358d825b0d33c01">60 percent</a> of the US population is under a heat advisory, flood warning, or flood watch.</li> <strong>Dispatches</strong><br><br><li> <b>The Books Briefing:</b> Books that show you how to do something new can lend life new meaning, <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/books-briefing-akiko-busch/674854/">Gal Beckerman writes</a> .</li> <em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://link.theatlantic.com/click/29767897.0/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYXRsYW50aWMuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLz91dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249YXRsYW50aWMtZGFpbHktbmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fY29udGVudD0yMDIyMTEyMQ/61813432e16c7128e42f4628B52865c35">Explore all of our newsletters here.</a></em><br><br> <strong>Evening Read</strong><br><br> You&#39;re Not Allowed to Have the Best Sunscreens in the World<br><br> <em>By Amanda Mull</em><br><br><p> At 36, I am just old enough to remember when sunscreen wasn&#39;t a big deal. My mom, despite being among the palest people alive, does not remember bringing it on our earliest vacations, or hearing any mention of sun protection by our pediatrician. The first memories I have of sunscreen are from the day camp that my brother and I attended in the 1990s, where we spent every day on a playground in the direct Georgia sun but were prompted to slather it on only once every two weeks, when we were bused to a community pool. On those days, mom dropped an ancient bottle of Coppertone, expiration date unknown, into my backpack, where I usually left it. In 2000, I started high school, just in time for the golden age of the tanning bed.</p><p> The preponderance of babies in rashguards and bucket hats that you now see at the beach shows how much has changed, and how quickly … Yet if sun protection, and specifically sunscreen, has become a <i>very</i> big deal in a relatively short amount of time, the UV blockers Americans are slathering on have barely evolved at all.</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2022/07/us-sunscreen-ingredients-outdated-technology-better-eu-asia/661433/">阅读全文。</a><br><br> <b>More From <em>The Atlantic</em></b><br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/israel-judicial-reform-and-protests-netanyahu/674849/">“</a> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/israel-judicial-reform-and-protests-netanyahu/674849/">After 30 years in Israel, I see my country differently.</a> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/israel-judicial-reform-and-protests-netanyahu/674849/">”</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/meta-microsoft-llama-2-ai-walled-garden-facebook/674824/">Tech companies&#39; friendly new strategy to destroy one another</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/meta-facebook-political-polarization-studies/674841/">So maybe Facebook didn&#39;t ruin politics.</a></li> <b>Culture Break</b><br><br> <b>Read.</b> On its 50th anniversary, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-first-jewish-catalog-richard-siegel/9780827600423?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>The Jewish Catalog</i></a> remains a case study in how grassroots efforts to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/the-jewish-catalog-50th-anniversary/674846/">modernize religious life</a> can succeed.<br><br> <b>Listen.</b> Before “Nothing Compares 2 U” made her a household name, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/sinead-oconnor-legacy-mandinka-song/674844/">a single from Sinéad O&#39;Connor&#39;s first album</a> established her as a creative force.<br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/free-daily-crossword-puzzle/">Play our daily crossword.</a><br><br><strong>聚苯乙烯</strong><br><br>This may sound weird, but I promise it&#39;s good: Try mixing amaro, grapefruit juice, and beer. I learned about this drink, “The Brunch Box,” from the aptly titled <i>Amaro</i> , a cocktail-recipe book by Brad Thomas Parsons that I received as a gift last summer. To make the drink, combine one ounce of Amaro Montenegro, one ounce of freshly squeezed grapefruit juice, and five ounces of beer, ideally lager. The crisp beer is rounded out by the herby amaro and tangy juice. I have long been skeptical of mixing beer into things (I have not tried one of those beer margaritas and hope to never do so). But this one is a treat.干杯!<br><br> — Lora<br><br> <i>Katherine Hu为本期通讯做出了贡献。</i><br><br> <em>When you buy a book using a link in this newsletter, we receive a commission. Thank you for supporting</em> The Atlantic <em>.</em><br><br> <small><em>This article has been updated to reflect a comment from Anheuser-Busch received after publication.</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 21:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/why-beer-sales-declining-seltzers/674862/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/why-beer-sales-declining-seltzers/674862/</item><item><title><![CDATA[Barbie Is Everything. Ken Is Everything Else.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>英雄。恶棍。因塞。战士。领导者。海滩。 Ken is not the star of <em>Barbie</em> , but he is its tragic, plastic heart. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/foIKWTn7yxm9P-n6uFr3fcC8tII=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/ken_hr/original.jpg" alt="瑞恩·高斯林在《芭比娃娃》中饰演肯" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Jaap Buitendijk / 华纳兄弟影业</figcaption></figure><small>这篇文章发表在《今日必读的一个故事》中，这是一份时事通讯，我们的编辑在其中推荐了《大西洋月刊<i data-stringify-type="italic">》周一至周五</i><i data-stringify-type="italic">必读的一篇文章</i>。 <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">在这里注册。</a></i></small><br><br> <strong><em>This article contains spoilers for the film</em></strong> <strong>Barbie <em>.</em></strong><br><br>本周早些时候，埃隆·马斯克宣布他将重塑自己的社交媒体平台：Twitter 现在简单来说就是 X。人们纷纷猜测为什么马斯克会用一个知名品牌来换取一封通常与拒绝和色情相关的信件： <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/elon-musk-rebrand-paypall-x-sounded-like-porn-site-twitter-2023-7">尽管</a>， 或许。或者也许——这是最荒谬的理论，因此也是最有可能的——那个给自己的车型命名为“S”、“3”、“X”和“Y”的人再次这样做是为了哈哈。据员工<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/24/technology/twitter-x-elon-musk.html">报告</a>，Twitter 更名为 X 后不久，其总部的会议室就被重新命名。马斯克尚未解雇的员工现在可以在名为“s3Xy”的会议室中规划民主化对话的未来。<br><br> X was released, as it happened, the same weekend that the Barbie movie was.这种巧合是雄辩的。毫无疑问， <em>《芭比娃娃》</em>是一部关于它的同名电影，也是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-greta-gerwig/674742/">对不可能的女性气质的探索</a>。但这也是一部关于肯的电影——在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-greta-gerwig-interview/674817/">导演格蕾塔·葛韦格的演绎</a>中，肯摆脱了芭比平淡配饰的地位，成为……一个权力痴迷的男孩，决心把世界变成他的玩物。<em>芭比</em>积极的营销活动中的任何元素都无法买到一位 52 岁的科技巨头所创造的相关性，当他不快速行动和/或打破事物时， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/elon-musks-humor-jokes-over-years-titter-420-69-2023-4">他会通过寻找新的方式将“69”写入其中来取乐</a>。公共记录。<br><br>许多专家认为，美国人生活在老​​年人统治之下：我们有太多的领导人在尝到了权力的滋味，然后花了几十年的时间来巩固它，却拒绝将自己的战利品让给其他任何人。然而，更广泛的事实更为可悲，因为它涉及那些无法应对权力责任的领导人，他们将我们的未来视为他们的玩具。几周来，马斯克和马克·扎克伯格一直在引发<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/01/technology/elon-musk-mark-zuckerberg-cage-match.html">外界猜测</a>，他们将通过电视转播的笼式比赛来解决业务分歧。美国人把我们的核密码交给了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/10/infantilization-of-a-president/542613/">一个布里奥尼襁褓中的小孩</a>。我们很可能<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/trump-2024-election-republican-primary-nomination-opponents/673882/">会再做一次</a>。我们生活在鲁莽的男孩国王的奴役之中。没有哪个虚构人物比一个看起来像男人但以男孩顽皮的欢乐将自己强加于世界的洋娃娃更能体现这种情况的荒谬性和悲剧性。肯需要关注。他发脾气。他播下混乱的种子。他威胁到整个秩序。他是<em>芭比</em>世界的塑料核心，也是我们世界的讽刺。<br><br>据说，芭比乐园是一个充满幼稚梦想的地方，安全、快乐、贫瘠、粉红色。在玩偶的土地上，“女孩的力量”并不是一个明显的谎言。相反，它是唯一存在的真理——支撑每一个无墙梦想之家的脚手架。它不仅塑造了芭比娃娃的职业生活（芭比总统、芭比物理学家、芭比医生），还塑造了他们对自己所处世界的感觉。芭比娃娃们自信、自我实现，而且总体上都很高兴，当然她们是这样：她们从来没有理由不这样。在《芭比乐园》中，芭比娃娃喜欢提醒自己，每一天都是“有史以来最好的一天”。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-greta-gerwig/674742/">阅读：芭比娃娃怎么了？</a><br><br>芭比乐园里有肯斯，但他们就像芭比娃娃本身一样，具有各种装饰性和多余性。肯一家住在哪里？他们开什么梦想之车？这样的问题毫无意义。在一个将财产视为个人成就感的代表的地方，肯一家似乎什么也没有。在一个将职业等同于身份的社会中，他们也没有明显的职业。不过，肯一家确实有一份工作：在芭比娃娃的闪亮表演中充当可靠的临时演员。当需要的时候，肯斯就会出现。他们很开朗。他们很有耐心。他们总是准备好穿上亮片，微笑着参加精心编排的舞蹈。与芭比乐园中的几乎所有其他东西一样，它们非常简单。因此，它们也非常无聊。<br><br>例外的是，对于其中一个：根据芭比乐园的二乘二逻辑，肯与刻板芭比配对。这个肯（由瑞恩·高斯林饰演）对自己的阶级地位感到不满。芭比乐园可能看起来像<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://collider.com/themyscira-wonder-woman-series-paradise-lost/">天堂岛</a>式的母系社会，亚马逊人高 11 英寸，由聚氯乙烯模制而成；然而，肯提醒我们乌托邦的残酷局限性。这部电影最明显的问题出现在早期，当刻板芭比（玛格特·罗比饰）发现自己受到人类状况的各种侮辱（不完美的棕色烤面包，死亡的想法，脂肪团）时。但早在芭比危机发生之前，芭比乐园的预制完美设施就并不完美。肯（Ken）首当其冲地犯了错误。他不仅仅是芭比娃娃的玩物；他也是芭比娃娃的玩物。他也是她随意残忍行为的接受者。 “你现在可以走了，”芭比告诉他，当他的脸垂下来时，她露出了微笑。后来：“我不想让你在这里。”<br><br>正是这些台词让<em>《芭比娃娃》</em>在上映后的几天里，遭到了一些对男性仇恨、性别歧视和“有毒女性气质”的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nypost.com/2023/07/24/if-i-made-a-movie-that-treated-women-the-way-barbie-treats-men-feminists-would-want-me-executed/">愤怒</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tmz.com/2023/07/22/barbie-attacked-right-wingers-anti-man-feminist-trash/">指控</a>。然而，这些批评忽略了——或者可能忽略了——即使在一部关于玩具的电影中也可能存在讽刺。芭比乐园的动态既复杂又简单：芭比在其范围内与世隔绝，在现实世界中代表了父权制的受益者。肯本质上代表了其他所有人。芭比对肯的不屑一顾，并不是刻薄的意思；而是她的意思。她对待他不假思索，因为她从来没有考虑过这些话——或者任何事情——可能会造成伤害。她从来不需要这样做。无论在她的社会还是在我们的社会，舒适都是一种奢侈。对于那些无法想象他人痛苦的人来说，人类世界的口号——以及将幼儿园课程中的善良和同理心转变为政治诉求的惨淡动态——毫无意义。<br><br>不过，它们对肯来说很有意义。在影片一开始，他就是这个塑料世界中最混乱的人类特征，是需求和希望的纠缠，最终是愤怒。在笑容满面的土地上，他皱起了眉头。被无尽的欢乐包围着，他感到疼痛。他感觉到有些事情非常不对劲。但他能做的就是感知。芭比乐园可能有总统、宪法和最高法院，但实际上它是非常非政治的。 （政治是对人类和冲突的回应；芭比乐园两者都不允许。）因此，没有语言或发泄他的挫败感——你可能会说，被一个<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://bookshop.org/p/books/the-feminine-mystique-anniversary-betty-friedan/8751751?ean=9780393934656&amp;ref=&amp;source=IndieBound&amp;title=The+Feminine+Mystique%3A+A+Norton+Critical+Edition+%28Norton+Critical+Editions%29">没有名字的问题所困扰</a>——肯只是摸索着度过他的困境。他的渴望让他受到了芭比乐园中陌生的东西的困扰：脆弱。<br><br><em>芭比</em>的魔力很大程度上归功于罗比和高斯林，以及他们作为演员将塑料与人类、真诚与阵营融为一体的能力。罗比的表演就其本身而言，是一个升华的问题。它捕捉到了使芭比娃娃成为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/05/tiny-shoulders-review-hulu/559277/">经久不衰的偶像和无尽争议的</a>许多元素，其中包括她难以企及的美丽、她快乐的天真、她的白皙、她的苗条，以及她提醒人们， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/08/jeffrey-epstein-and-the-myth-of-the-underage-woman/596140/">即使是孩子也会受到女性不断变化的需求的困扰。</a> 。高斯林也发现了类似的细微差别，但方向相反：臭名昭著的是，肯是一个因缺席而被定义为加号的人。高斯林填补了这个空白。为此，他将娃娃的一种基本讽刺元素——芭比和肯是经常被误认为成年人的青少年——融入到他的表演中。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/08/jeffrey-epstein-and-the-myth-of-the-underage-woman/596140/">阅读：“未成年女性”的神话</a><br><br>在高斯林的笔下，肯生活在各种情绪之中，而这些情绪总是超出他的控制范围。他时而暴躁，时而充满可能性，时而冲动，时而自我意识。这也意味着，这个尖嘴娃娃在很多方面都是一个非常典型的青少年。芭比刚刚被人类的情感所困扰，她哭得震惊了自己——先是一滴眼泪，然后是洪水般的泪水。高斯林的肯也哭了。但他的不和谐具有典型的男性特征。他勃然大怒。尽管他对此一无所知，但他觉得自己有权进行性行为。他非常关心其他人对他的看法。 “你不能让我在肯面前显得不酷！”他对着芭比哭泣，眼中闪烁着惊慌。<br><br>在电影的早期场景中，肯对芭比发脾气。他就在那里，散发着看着我的渴望。他就像罗密欧的诗歌或<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1GoH3M9Kb4g">劳埃德·多布勒的音箱</a>一样，将爱情变成了一场表演。他如此彻底地将自己的生活定位在芭比身上，以至于不久之后，他就成为了肯在芭比乐园中不能成为的一件事：一种障碍。<br><br>肯和芭比一样，对自己的需要感到不满。但《芭比乐园》并没有给他提供其他选择。<em>她就是一切；他只是肯</em>。这就是这个世界的方式。高斯林的表演体现了这一切。然后，它有力地使事情升级：肯对芭比的需求变得如此强烈，以至于凝结成暴力。很快，他充满希望的微笑就变成了冷笑。他对芭比娃娃的顽固渴望——以及他无法接受她的不感兴趣——开始唤起非独者的残酷权利。他的困境成为其他人的威胁。<br><br>这令人不安，洋娃娃变得危险。这就是它如此有效的原因。影片的大部分内容都让芭比和肯踏上了一段模仿青春期的旅程：离开了受保护、玩耍和轻松梦想的土地，他们陷入了人类世界的现实——以及成年期的艰难交易。玩偶必须在一个不乏语言来描述其政治状况的地方航行：<em>父权制</em>、<em>边缘化</em>、<em>物化</em>、<em>压迫</em>。<br><br>肯喜欢它。走在洛杉矶的街道上——他穿着流苏覆盖的西式服装，这是由于情节中的一次偶然事件而启发的服装选择——他开始昂首阔步。他第一次感到被尊重、被钦佩、被看见。与此同时，芭比娃娃是一个先感受到——然后又害怕——自己性别的脆弱性的人。<em>芭比</em>最好的笑话之一是肯回到芭比乐园后，用吉他为她弹了一首歌——他明确表示，这不是<em>给</em>芭比唱歌，而是<em>对着</em>她唱歌。肯低声哼唱，被他浪漫的手势所吸引，紧紧抓住芭比的目光，不肯放开。这一切的荒谬性被他选择的那首歌的歌词所戳穿——这首歌在现实世界中成为热门歌曲：<em>我想把你推来推去，好吧我会，好吧我会/我想把你推倒，好吧我会，好吧，我会</em>……<br><br>青春期是一个极端的时期。肯在男人的世界里经历了男子气概，他对新的处境做出了少年般的欢乐。当他像一个孩子一样沉浸在周围的环境中时——总是充满活力地沉浸在周围的图像和信息中——他首先直觉地认为，男子气概是现实世界中的一切，其次，男子气概必须与马有关。 （他总结道，父权制是“骑在马上的男人管理一切”的制度。）他对洛基·巴尔博亚和比尔·克林顿的形象着迷，对那些在健身房里互相击掌的家伙着迷。回到芭比乐园，他吸取了从现实中学到的教训，接管了芭比的梦想屋。他的 Mojo Dojo Casa House 是一个单身汉公寓和一家酒吧，从整体美学来看，是对约翰·韦恩 (John Wayne) 对美国男性气质的影响的致敬。显然，它的装饰以大量的马为特色。<br><br>肯的​​过激行为很有趣，也很愚蠢，而且，除了偷窃房屋的事情之外，还很容易引起共鸣。像任何青少年一样，肯正在弄清楚自己是谁，并尝试着世界的各种可能性。但他的不成熟并没有得到遏制，这就是它的问题。相反，他青少年时期对待世界的态度也影响到了其他人。很快——对于任何一个近年来关注美国政治的人来说，这个情节的转折同时也是一个转折——肯正试图改写芭比乐园的宪法。<br><br>肯试图将自己融入芭比乐园的政治生活，这是一种不祥的正义。这是零和世界问题的零和解决方案。多年来，肯娃娃一直被称为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/22/style/ken-barbie-doll-biography-cec/index.html">生殖器被严重缩短的水滴</a>”、“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.esquire.com/uk/culture/a44285254/the-history-of-ken-barbie/">一个令人不舒服的反男子气概的象征</a>”，以及——高斯林在<em>芭比娃娃</em>的宣传之旅中——“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2022/07/22/entertainment/ryan-gosling-ken-barbie-doll-cec/index.html">一个配件，甚至不是一个装饰品”。最酷的之一</a>。”当肯出现在 2010 年的<em>《玩具总动员 3》</em>中时，他发现自己收到了下面这句话：“你这个穿着阿斯科特的粉红鼻子！你不是一个玩具……你是一个有腿的钱包！”<br><br>这种侮辱变得更加侮辱性，因为它是由一个四肢可拆卸且有愤怒管理问题的块茎<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A-H9-CLfOWg">发出的</a>。但土豆头先生只是说出了大家都知道的事情：肯的定义事实是肯是由芭比娃娃定义的。仅凭这一点就很难不为这个家伙感到难过。对于许多<em>芭比娃娃</em>的观众来说，他的困境可能非常熟悉。正如我的同事雪莉·李（Shirley Li） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/">所写的</a>那样，影片中的一个关键时刻来自其中一位人类主角格洛丽亚（亚美莉卡·费雷拉饰），她在演讲中讲述了作为一个人所面临的挑战和完全的非理性，她在演讲中召唤了一生的挫败感。女人生活在一个由男人塑造的世界里。不过，另一个关键时刻来自肯。电影快结束了，他终于得到了他真正想要的一件事：芭比正在听他说话。他告诉她，为了别人的光芒而变得黯淡是什么感觉。然后他又补充了一句：“感觉不太好，不是吗？”<br><br>阅读：理解<a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/"><em>芭比</em></a> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/">电影的</a> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/">令人惊讶的关键</a><br><br>那些指责<em>芭比娃娃</em>厌男的评论家可能想再看一次，如果他们真的看过的话。肯的​​台词有效地为格洛丽亚的演讲添加了标点符号。它做了我们当前的政治口号恳求我们做的事情，但徒劳无功：它产生同理心。肯发现，他其实并不想要政治权力；他只是想获得政治权力。这是很多工作。 （此外，令人失望的是，马只是“人的延伸器”。）他真正寻求的是按照自己的方式弄清楚自己是谁的能力。肯真的想要芭比娃娃吗？正如电影所暗示的那样，他愿意与另一个肯配对吗？如果他的身份比芭比和海滩更广泛，他会选择做什么？<br><br>在影片的结尾，肯不再只是一个了解人类世界生活的洋娃娃；他也是一个懂得在别人的故事中被当作临时演员的感觉的人。在他身上，塑造并限制我们政治可能性的辩论变得优雅而直接。肯是一个被剥夺了充分人格尊严的人。无论你的世界观如何，无论你的具体情况如何，无论你对<em>父权制</em>这个词有什么感受，这都是一种公然的不公正形式。<br><br>但在故事的结尾，肯也是一个逃离了发展停滞的人。他已经体现了<em>芭比娃娃</em>的核心思想之一：父权制是一种深刻的不成熟形式。它会导致孩子气。也是由此产生的结果。不过，我们有一个充满希望的理由，因为我们真正的男孩子们一直在努力将世界改造成他们的魔力道场之家：对于肯来说，不成熟变成了大多数人的样子——通往更好的道路上的一个阶段。肯没有变成人类。然而，他确实长大了。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 13:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-ken/674852/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-ken/674852/</item></channel></rss>